e are several versions of the mile progression before that year. One version starts with [[Richard Webster, 1st Viscount Alverstone|Richard Webster]] (GBR) who ran 4:36.5 in 1865, surpassed by Chinnery in 1868.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berkshiresports.org/index.php?ID=milerecordprogression |title=World Mile Record Progression |publisher=Berkshire Sports |date= |accessdate=2011-09-04}}</ref>\n\nAnother variation of the amateur record progression pre-1862 is as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stat.colostate.edu/~jah/teach/st540/data/mile.info |title=Progression of world record times for males |work=sta.colostate.edu |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Time !!Athlete !!Nationality !!Date !!Venue\n|-\n|'''4:52'''|| [[Cadet Marshall]] || {{GBR|1801}} || 2 September 1852|| Addiscome \n|-\n|'''4:45'''|| [[Thomas Finch (runner)|Thomas Finch]] || {{GBR|1801}} || 3 November 1858|| Oxford \n|-\n|'''4:45'''|| [[St. Vincent Hammick]] || {{GBR|1801}} || 15 November 1858|| Oxford \n|-\n|'''4:40'''|| [[Gerald Surman]] || {{GBR|1801}} || 24 November 1859|| Oxford \n|-\n|'''4:33'''|| [[George Farran]] || {{GBR|1801}} || 23 May 1862|| Dublin \n|}\n\n===IAAF era===\n\nThe first '''[[world record]]''' in the '''mile for men''' ([[athletics (sport)|athletics]]) was recognized by the International Amateur Athletics Federation, now known as the [[International Association of Athletics Federations]], in 1913.\n\nTo June 21, 2009, the IAAF has ratified 32 world records in the event.<ref name=iaaf>\n{{cite web\n |title       = 12th IAAF World Championships In Athletics: IAAF Statistics Handbook. Berlin 2009.\n |url         = http://www.iaaf.org/mm/document/competitions/competition/05/15/63/20090706014834_httppostedfile_p345-688_11303.pdf\n |publisher   = IAAF Media & Public Relations Department\n |location    = Monte Carlo\n |pages       = Pages 546, 549\u201350\n |format      = PDF\n |year        = 2009\n |accessdate  = August 4, 2009\n |archiveurl  = h