39 || London \n|-\n|'''5:11.0 '''|| Anne Oliver || {{GBR}} || 14 June 1952 || London \n|-\n|'''5:09.8 '''|| Enid Harding || {{GBR}} || 4 June 1953 || London \n|-\n|'''5:08.0 '''|| Anne Oliver || {{GBR}} || 12 September 1953 || Consett \n|-\n|'''5:02.6 '''|| [[Diane Leather]] || {{GBR}} || 30 September 1953 || London \n|-\n|'''5:00.3 '''|| [[Edith Treybal]] || {{ROM}} || 1 November 1953 || Timi\u0219oara \n|-\n|'''5:00.2 '''||[[Diane Leather]] || {{GBR}} || 26 May 1954 || Birmingham \n|-\n|'''4:59.6 '''|| [[Diane Leather]] || {{GBR}} || 29 May 1954 || Birmingham \n|-\n|'''4:50.8 '''|| [[Diane Leather]] || {{GBR}} || 24 May 1955 || London \n|-\n|'''4:45.0 '''|| [[Diane Leather]] || {{GBR}} || 21 September 1955 || London \n|-\n|'''4:41.4 '''|| [[Marise Chamberlain]] || {{NZL}} || 8 December 1962 || Perth \n|-\n|'''4:39.2 '''|| [[Anne Smith (middle-distance runner)|Anne Smith]] || {{GBR}} || 13 May 1967 || London \n|}\n\n===Women's IAAF era===\n\nThe first '''[[world record]]''' in the '''mile for women''' ([[athletics (sport)|athletics]]) was recognized by the International Amateur Athletics Federation, now known as the [[International Association of Athletics Federations]], in 1967.\n\nTo June 21, 2009, the IAAF has ratified 13 world records in the event.<ref name=iaaf2>\n{{cite web\n |title=12th IAAF World Championships In Athletics: IAAF Statistics Handbook. Berlin 2009. \n |url=http://www.iaaf.org/mm/document/competitions/competition/05/15/63/20090706014834_httppostedfile_p345-688_11303.pdf \n |publisher=IAAF Media & Public Relations Department \n |location=Monte Carlo \n |pages=Pages 546, 642 \n |format=PDF \n |year=2009 \n |accessdate=August 4, 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629134819/http://www.iaaf.org/mm/document/competitions/competition/05/15/63/20090706014834_httppostedfile_p345-688_11303.pdf \n |archivedate=June 29, 2011 \n}}\n</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Time !!Auto !!Athlete !!Nationality !!Date !!Venue\n|-\n|'''4:37.0'''|| || [[Anne Smith (middle-distance runner)|Anne Smith]] || {{GBR}} || 3 June 1967<ref name=iaaf2/> || London \n|-\n|'''4:36.8'''|| || [[Maria Gommers]] || {{NED}} || 14 June 1969<ref name=iaaf2/> || Leicester \n|-\n|'''4:35.3'''|| || [[Ellen Tittel]] || {{FRG}} || 20 August 1971<ref name=iaaf2/> || Sittard \n|-\n|'''4:29.5'''|| || [[Paola Pigni]] || {{ITA}} || 8 August 1973<ref name=iaaf2/> || Viareggio \n|-\n|'''4:23.8'''|| || [[Natalia M\u0103r\u0103\u0219escu]] || {{ROM}} || 21 May 1977<ref name=iaaf2/> || Bucharest \n|-\n|'''4:22.1'''|| 4:22.09 || [[Natalia M\u0103r\u0103\u0219escu]] || {{ROM}} || 27 January 1979<ref name=iaaf2/>|| Auckland \n|-\n|'''4:21.7'''|| 4:21.68 || [[Mary Slaney|Mary Decker]] || {{USA}} || 26 January 1980<ref name=iaaf2/>|| Auckland \n|-\n|'''4:20.89'''|||| [[Lyudmila Veselkova]] || {{URS}} || 12 September 1981<ref name=iaaf2/>||  Bologna \n|-\n|'''4:18.08'''|| ||  [[Mary Decker|Mary Decker-Tabb]] || {{USA}} || 9 July 1982<ref name=iaaf2/>|| Paris \n|-\n|'''4:17.44'''|| ||  [[Maricica Puic\u0103]] || {{ROM}} || 9 September 1982<ref name=iaaf2/>|| Rieti \n|-\n|'''4:16.71'''||||  [[Mary Decker|Mary Decker-Slaney]] || {{USA}} || 21 August 1985<ref name=iaaf2/>|| Z\u00fcrich \n|-\n|'''4:15.61'''|| ||  [[Paula Ivan]] || {{ROM}} || 10 July 1989<ref name=iaaf2/>|| Nice \n|-\n|'''4:12.56'''|| || [[Svetlana Masterkova]] || {{RUS}} || 14 August 1996<ref name=iaaf2/>|| Z\u00fcrich \n|-\n|'''4:12.33'''||  || [[Sifan Hassan]] || {{NED}} || 12 July 2019|| Monaco \n|}\n\nThe \"Time\" column indicates the ratified mark; the \"Auto\" column indicates a fully automatic time that was also recorded in the event when hand-timed marks were used for official records, or which was the basis for the official mark, rounded to the 10th of a second, depending on the rules then in place. \n\nThe IAAF recognized times to the hundredth of a second starting in 1981.<ref name=iaaf2/>\n\nDecker ran 4:17.55 in Houston on 16 February 1980, and [[Natalya Artyomova]] (Soviet Union) ran 4:15.8 in Leningrad on 6 August 1984, but neither time was ratified by the IAAF.\n\n==Women's Indoor==\n\n===Women Indoor Pre-IAAF===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Time !!Athlete !!Nationality !!Date !!Venue\n|-\n| '''5:17.2''' || [[Brenda Cook]] || {{GBR}} ||  February 5, 1966 || [[Cosford, Shropshire|Cosford]] {{GBR}}\n|-\n| '''5:03.6''' || [[Joyce Smith]] || {{GBR}} ||  February 12, 1966 || [[Cosford, Shropshire|Cosford]] {{GBR}}\n|-\n| '''4:52.0''' || [[Doris Brown]] || {{USA}} ||  February 19, 1966 || [[Vancouver, British Columbia|Vancouver]] {{CAN}}\n|-\n| '''4:40.4''' || [[Doris Brown]] || {{USA}} ||  February 18, 1967 || [[Vancouver, British Columbia|Vancouver]] {{CAN}}\n|-\n| '''4:38.5''' || [[Debbie Heald]] || {{USA}} ||  March 17, 1972 || [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] {{USA}}\n|-\n| '''4:35.6''' || [[Francie Larrieu]] || {{USA}} ||  February 17, 1973 || [[San Diego]] {{USA}}\n|-\n| '''4:34.6''' || [[Francie Larrieu]] || {{USA}} ||  February 2, 1974 || [[Seattle]] {{USA}}\n|-\n| '''4:29.0''' || [[Francie Larrieu]] || {{USA}} ||  February 15, 1975 || [[San Diego]] {{USA}}\n|-\n| '''4:28.5''' || [[Francie Larrieu]] || {{USA}} ||  March 3, 1975 || [[Richmond, Virginia|Richmond]] {{USA}}\n|-\n| '''4:24.6''' || [[Mary Decker]] || {{USA}} ||  January 22, 1982 || [[Los Angeles]] {{USA}}\n|-\n| '''4:21.47''' || [[Mary Decker]] || {{USA}} ||  February 12, 1982 || [[New York City|New York]] {{USA}}\n|}\n\n===Women Indoor IAAF era===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Time !!Athlete !!Nationality !!Date !!Venue\n|-\n|'''4:20.5'''|| [[Mary Decker]] || {{USA}} ||  February 19, 1982 || [[San Diego]] {{USA}}\n|-\n|'''4:18.86''' || [[Doina Melinte]] || {{ROU}} ||  February 13, 1988 || [[East Rutherford]] {{USA}}\n|-\n|'''4:17.14''' || [[Doina Melinte]] || {{ROU}} ||  February 9, 1990 || [[East Rutherford]] {{USA}}\n|-\n|'''4:13.31''' || [[Genzebe Dibaba]] || {{ETH}} ||  February 17, 2016 || [[Stockholm]] {{SWE}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[1500 metres world record progression]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Cite book|last=Bascomb|first=Neil|title=The Perfect Mile|year=2004|publisher=Willow|isbn=978-0-0071737-3-0}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Bryant|first=John|title=3:59.4 The Quest To Break The Four Minute Mile|year=2004|publisher=Hutchinson|isbn=978-0-0918003-3-8}}\n*{{Cite book|last1=Nelson|first1=Cordner|last2=Quercetani|first2=Roberto|title=The Milers|year=1985|publisher=Tafnews Press|isbn=0-911521-15-1}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Phillips|first=Bob|title=3:59.4 The Quest For The Four-Minute Mile|year=2004|publisher=Parrs Wood Press|isbn=978-1-9031584-9-4}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stat.colostate.edu/~jah/teach/st540/data/mile.info ''Runner's World'' data]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080329011913/http://runningtimes.com/rt/articles/?id=6385 ''Running Times'' Magazine data]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090607005109/http://user.uni-frankfurt.de/~khg/Rekorde/progtkwm.htm Frankfurt University] {{in lang|de}} ([[Internet Archive]])\n*[http://www.apulanta.fi/matti/yu/wrprogr_Women.html#Mile Women's progression]\n*[http://www.saunalahti.fi/~sut/eng/wwrrun.html#mile Another women's mile progression]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090829134934/http://user.uni-frankfurt.de/~khg/Rekorde/progtkww.htm Frankfurt University (Women's progression)] {{in lang|de}} (Internet Archive)\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uz3ZLpCmKCM Clips of Banister's 4 minute mile]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XvCsj7eJKKA Video of current Men's world record by Hicham El Guerrouj]\n\n{{Athletics record progressions}}\n\n[[Category:World athletics record progressions]]\n[[Category:Mile races]]\n", "name_user": "162.245.50.17", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile_run_world_record_progression"}
{"title_page": "Dole Food Company", "text_new": "''Italic text''{{Infobox company\n| name                = Dole Food Company, Inc.\n| logo                = Dole Logo.svg\n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| genre               = \n| foundation          = <!-- this parameter modifies \"Founded\" -->{{start date and age|1851|6|2}}<ref name=\"dole\">[http://www.dole.com/CompanyInfo/About/History.jsp Dole: Company History] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117163821/http://www.dole.com/CompanyInfo/About/History.jsp |date=November 17, 2007 }} (Retrieved November 29, 2007)</ref><br>[[Kingdom of Hawaii]]\n| founder             = [[Samuel Northrup Castle]] <br> [[Amos Starr Cooke]]\n| location_city       = [[Westlake Village, California|Westlake Village]], [[California]]\n| location_country    = U.S.\n| location            = <!-- this parameter modifies \"Headquarters\" -->\n| origins             = \n| key_people          = [[David H. Murdock]]<br>[[Chairman]]<br>[[Carl McCann]]<br>[[Deputy Chairman]]<br>[[Johan Lind\u00e9n]]<br>[[President, COO, CEO]]\n| industry            = [[Agribusiness]]\n| products            = [[Fruit]]<br>[[Vegetables]]<br>Other food products\n| services            = \n| revenue             = [[United States dollar|US$]]4.566 billion (2019) <ref>{{cite web |last1=totalproduce.com/investors |title=Preliminary Results 2019 |url=https://investors.totalproduce.com/~/media/Files/T/Total-Produce-IR/documents/presentations/2020/2019-preliminary-results-presentation.pdf |website=Totalproduce.com/investors |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_income    = \n| Operating_profit          = $173.8 million (2019)<ref>{{cite web |last1=totalproduce.com/investors |title=Preliminary Results 2019 |url=https://investors.totalproduce.com/~/media/Files/T/Total-Produce-IR/documents/presentations/2020/2019-preliminary-results-presentation.pdf |website=Totalproduce.com/investors |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n| num_employees       = 34,500 (2011)<ref name=\"busweek\">{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=259280 |title=Dole Food Company Inc.: Private Company Information \u2013 Businessweek |publisher=Investing.businessweek.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref>\n| parent              = \n| divisions           = \n| subsid              = \n| owner               = \n| slogan              = \n| homepage            = {{URL|www.dole.com}}\n| dissolved           = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Dole Food Company, Inc.''' is an [[United States|American]] [[agricultural]] [[multinational corporation]] headquartered in [[Westlake Village, California]]. The company is the largest [[food industry|producer]] of [[fruit]] and [[vegetables]] in the world, operating with 74,300 full-time and seasonal employees who are responsible for over 300 products in 90 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/10/10303.html |title=Dole Food Company, Inc. Company Profile \u2013 Yahoo! Finance |publisher=Biz.yahoo.com |date=2012-09-25 |accessdate=2012-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116165632/http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/10/10303.html |archivedate=2013-01-16 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoovers.com/company/Dole_Food_Company_Inc/rfyfyi-1.html |title=&#124; Company Profile from Hoover's |publisher=Hoovers.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref> Dole markets such food items as [[bananas]], [[pineapples]], [[grapes]], [[strawberries]], salads, and other fresh and frozen fruits and juices. Dole owns a shipping line, Dole Ocean Cargo Express.\n\nDole's chairman founded the [[Dole Nutrition Institute]], a nutritional research and education foundation.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:DolePineapplePlantation.jpg|thumb|left|Dole Plantation on [[Oahu, Hawaii]].]]\nThe company traces its origin to the 1851 establishment of [[Castle & Cooke]] by missionaries [[Samuel Northrup Castle]] and [[Amos Starr Cooke]]. Castle & Cooke rapidly became one of the largest companies in Hawaii, investing in shipping, railroad construction, sugar production and seafood packing. The other half of Dole's corporate heritage, the '''Hawaiian Pineapple Company''', was founded in 1901 by [[James Dole]], who opened his first pineapple plantation in the central plateau of the Hawaiian island of [[Oahu]]. [[Sanford Dole]], the cousin of James, had been president of the [[Republic of Hawaii]] from 1894 after the [[overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii]] (her last monarch, [[Liliuokalani|Queen Lili{{okina}}uokalani]]), and first governor of the [[Territory of Hawaii]] until 1903.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://archives1.dags.hawaii.gov/gsdl/collect/governme/index/assoc/HASHb5a9/8f7a506f.dir/Dole,%20Sanford%20Ballard.jpg |title= Dole, Sanford Ballard office record |work= state archives digital collections |publisher= state of Hawaii |accessdate= 2010-01-20 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120306203149/http://archives1.dags.hawaii.gov/gsdl/collect/governme/index/assoc/HASHb5a9/8f7a506f.dir/Dole%2C%20Sanford%20Ballard.jpg |archivedate= 2012-03-06 }}</ref>\nThe annexation of Hawaii to the United States made selling agricultural products to the mainland much more profitable, since they would never be subject to import [[tariff]]s.\n\nIn 1932, Castle & Cooke purchased a 21% interest in the Hawaiian Pineapple Company. In the 1960s, Castle & Cooke acquired the remainder of the Hawaiian Pineapple Company and the [[Standard Fruit Company]]. In 1976, it acquired Bud Antle Inc., a California-based lettuce and celery farmer; it was renamed Dole Fresh Vegetables in 1989. The company was renamed \"The Dole Food Company, Inc\" in 1991. Castle & Cooke Inc, a [[real estate]] company, was spun off in 1995; it is currently operating as a subsidiary of Flexi-Van Leasing, Inc. Dole's [[Waialua Sugar Mill]] closed in 1996.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Star-Bulletin| first = Russ Lynch| title = Waialua closing the book on Oahu's sugar industry \u2013 Today is the last day of harvesting and by Saturday the shutdown will be complete| work = Honolulu Star-Bulletin (HI)| accessdate = 2018-04-22| date = 1996-10-02| url = http://infoweb.newsbank.com/resources/doc/nb/news/1296CDE56F67D958?p=NewsBank|via=[[NewsBank]]}}</ref> Dole acquired Coastal Berry in 2004 and SunnyRidge Farms in 2011 to enter the berry business.<ref>[http://vegetablegrowersnews.com/news/dole-food-acquires-coastal-berry/ Dole Food Acquires Coastal Berry]</ref><ref>[http://www.growingproduce.com/uncategorized/dole-acquires-sunnyridge-farm/ Dole Acquires SunnyRidge Farm]</ref>\n\n[[File:Dole freighter in San Juan, Puerto Rico.jpg|thumb|200px|Dole freighter sailing out of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]]]\nIt was then the third largest producer and U.S. importer of bananas. Dole and [[Chiquita]] remain the top two U.S. banana companies as of 2011. In 2011, the company reported $7.2 billion in annual [[revenue]].<ref name=\"hoovers\"/>\n\nDole operates plantations throughout [[Central America|Central]] and [[South America]], and in the [[Asia-Pacific]] region, with plantations in the [[Philippines]] and two packing plants in [[Thailand]], [[Hua Hin]] and [[Chumphon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dole.co.th/en/#contact-us |title=Locations of Dole Food Company in Thailand |year=2012 |publisher=Dole Food Company |accessdate=9 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930002306/http://www.dole.co.th/en#contact-us |archive-date=30 September 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAs part of a major restructuring in 2012, Dole agreed to sell its worldwide packaged foods and Asian fresh produce businesses to Japanese trading house [[Itochu]] for $1.7 billion in cash. The transaction paid down a large amount of Dole's debt and refocused the company's business on fresh fruit and vegetables.<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan's Itochu to buy Dole Food businesses for $1.7 billion|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/09/18/us-dolefood-itochu-idUSBRE88H01L20120918|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> The businesses acquired by Itochu continue to use the Dole brand and are owned by Dole International Holdings, a Tokyo-based subsidiary of Itochu.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dole Business|url=http://www.itochu.co.jp/en/business/food/project/10/|publisher=Itochu Corporation|accessdate=2 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908001600/http://www.itochu.co.jp/en/business/food/project/10/|archivedate=8 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Dole announced that CEO David Murdock would acquire the outstanding stock of the company for $1.2 billion.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323585604579008502351303672 | title=Dole Food Agrees to $1.2 Billion Buyout Offer | work=The Wall Street Journal | date=August 12, 2013 | accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> The sale closed in October 2013, but was challenged by shareholders who argued that the company was undervalued, based in part on underestimated cost savings from the 2012 sale of the Asia business. In 2015, the [[Delaware Chancery Court]] awarded $148 million in damages to the former shareholders, on the grounds that Murdock and chief operating officer C. Michael Carter had misled shareholders regarding the finances of the company.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hoffman|first1=Liz|title=Dole Executives Ordered to Pay $148 Million in Buyout Lawsuit|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/dole-executives-ordered-to-pay-148-million-in-buyout-lawsuit-1440686542|accessdate=2 September 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=27 August 2015}}</ref> Dole, which had moved its corporate registration from Hawaii to Delaware in 2001, became an outspoken critic of Delaware corporate law as a result of this litigation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hoffman|first1=Liz|title=Dole and Other Companies Sour on Delaware as Corporate Haven|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/dole-and-other-companies-sour-on-delaware-as-corporate-haven-1438569507|accessdate=2 September 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=2 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nDole is a vertically integrated producer, owning plantations in Central America.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wang|first1=Dan|title=Meet Dole, the World's Full-Stack Banana Company|url=https://www.flexport.com/blog/why-dole-owns-container-ships/|publisher=Flexport|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref>  It operates a fleet of 19 container ships<ref>{{cite web|title=Vessels|url=http://www.doleoceancargo.com/vessels.html|publisher=Dole Ocean Cargo|accessdate=5 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206002505/http://www.doleoceancargo.com/vessels.html|archive-date=6 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> that are specially equipped to support refrigerated containers and have their own cranes instead of relying on port infrastructure.\n\n===Management===\nIn April 2017, Johan Linden was named [[chief executive officer]], in addition to his role as President,<ref>{{cite web|title=Executive Profile: Johan Linden, Chief Executive Officer and President, Dole Food Company, Inc.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=290561769&privcapId=259280&previousCapId=259280&previousTitle=Dole%20Food%20Company%20Inc.|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=31 January 2018|date=January 2018}}</ref> and Johan Malmavist was [[chief financial officer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Ranking of America's Largest Private Companies: Dole Food|url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/dole-food/|work=Forbes|accessdate=31 January 2018|date=2018}}</ref>\n\n===Products===\n[[File:Dolejf2103.JPG|thumb|220px|right|Fresh ripe Dole pineapples ([[Philippines]])]]\nIncluding the original [[pineapple]], Dole distributes fresh plant foods in the forms of  whole fruits, whole vegetables,  berries, and fresh-cut vegetables. \nPackaged products include fruit bowls, fruit bowls in gel, fruit in plastic jars, fruit parfaits, fruit crisps, dates, raisins, and canned fruits. \nFrozen products include berries, tropical fruits, and fruit bars.\nJuices are sold chilled, frozen, or canned.\nSalad products include greens, salad kits, and shreds.<ref>{{cite web |title= All About Dole Products |work= official web site |publisher= Dole Food, Inc |url= http://www.dole.com/EatRightLanding/EatRtProductIndex/tabid/892/Default.aspx |accessdate= September 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 Dole bought several growers in [[Colombia]] and became the largest distributor of fresh-cut flowers in the US. However, by 2008 the flower business was losing money, and it was bought in January 2009 by a group of private investors.\n\n===Corporate headquarters===\nIn 1994, Dole announced that it would finalize its plans to build its world headquarters on a {{convert|30|acre|m2|adj=on}} site owned by the company, located north of the [[Ventura Freeway]] in [[Westlake Village, California|Westlake Village]], California. The decision had been delayed by groundwater contamination tests and reviewing of possible site plan revisions. Having submitted its plans for final approval by the Westlake Village City Council on February 9, 1994,<ref>{{cite news |title= Dole gets ready to turn first shovel of headquarters dirt: plans are set to go to Westlake Village City Council |work= [[Los Angeles Business Journal]] |date= January 31, 1994 |url= http://www.allbusiness.com/north-america/united-states-california-metro-areas/426968-1.html |accessdate= September 15, 2010 }}</ref> Dole completed construction and opened its new world headquarters building in May 1999.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[Image:Pineapple maze 1.JPG|thumb|Dole Plantation Pineapple Maze]]\n\nThe [[Guinness Book of World Records]] (2007) lists the pineapple maze at the Dole Plantation in [[Oahu, Hawaii|Honolulu, Hawaii]] as the world's largest [[maze]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dole-plantation.com/Maze/maze.aspx |title=Dole Plantation \u2013 Hawaii's Complete Pineapple Experience \u2013 Maze |accessdate=2008-02-14 |publisher=Dole Plantation, Inc. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080121014452/http://www.dole-plantation.com/Maze/maze.aspx |archivedate=2008-01-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Dole Nutrition Institute]] (DNI) was founded by David H. Murdock in 2003 to \"Feed the World with Knowledge\" through research and education regarding the health benefits of a plant-based diet.\n\n==Mascot==\n[[File:Dole Mascots (41848912380) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Bobby Banana and Pinellopy Pineapple in San Diego in 2018]]\n'''Bobby Banana''' is a [[mascot]] of Dole Food Company and the leader of the SuperKids (children who regularly eat five to nine fruits and vegetables every day).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dole.com/WhatsASuperkid/tabid/824/Default.aspx |title=WhatsASuperkid |publisher=Dole |date= |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref>  He is an [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[banana]] who appears in Dole comics and games for children, along with friends Courtney Cauliflower, Mia Mango, Pinellopy Pineapple, and Gavin Grape, all of whom are also anthropomorphic fruits and vegetables.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dole.com/DoleFlashHomePage/tabid/972/Default.aspx#/superkids/ |title=Homepage |publisher=Dole |date=2010-06-21 |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985 and 1986, the Dole banana was featured as the official banana of the Pittsburg State University (KS) Gorillas' athletic programs.  The project was the brainchild of then Pitt State radiosports play-by-play voice Scott Burton.  The introduction of the Dole banana as the official banana of the Gorillas delighted then Athletic Director David Suenram and Pittsburg State University sports fans alike.  The head football coach at the time of the promotion was Dennis Franchione.  Dole provided company trinkets for fan giveaways and the popularity of the Dole banana thrived in southeast Kansas and southwest Missouri (Joplin) during the promotion's two-year run.\n\n==Advertising==\n\nFor a number of years, the [[country music]] artist [[Kenny Rogers]] advertised Dole's products on television. He would often be accompanied by his then wife, Marianne. Dole also sponsored several of Rogers' concert tours.\n\n==Food safety==\n\n===2005 ''E. coli'' outbreak===\nIn 2005, 23 people in [[Minnesota]] were sickened with [[E. coli O157:H7|''E. coli'' O157:H7]]. The source of the [[bacteria]] was found to be Dole brand bagged lettuce.<ref name=\"Murphey\">{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208032833/http://www.producenews.com/storydetail.cfm?ID=5449 |archivedate=February 8, 2009 |url=http://www.producenews.com/storydetail.cfm?ID=5449 |title=Minnesota finds ''E. coli'' in lettuce bags |first=Joan |last=Murphy |location=Oradell, NJ, USA |work=The Produce News |issn=0032-969X|oclc=4109334|date=October 17, 2005 |accessdate=October 5, 2012|via=[[Wayback Machine]]}}</ref>\n\n===2006 ''E. coli'' outbreak===\n{{main|2006 North American E. coli O157:H7 outbreak in spinach}}\nIn 2006, an ''E. coli'' outbreak that caused over 200 people to become ill and killed 3 more was linked to bagged [[spinach]] sold by Dole. The spinach was processed by Natural Selection Foods in [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.about-ecoli.com/ecoli_outbreaks/news/e-coli-found-in-water-wild-pig-near-california-spinach-farm/ |title=''E. coli'' Food Poisoning |publisher=About-ecoli.com |date=2006-10-27 |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref>\n\n===2007 ''E. coli'' recall===\nIn September 2007, random testing conducted by the [[Canadian Food Inspection Agency]] detected ''E. coli'' O157:H7 bacteria in Dole's \"Hearts Delight\" packaged salad. The company issued a recall for the product, which had been distributed in Ontario, Quebec, New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, and Prince Edward Island in Canada, and in Illinois, Indiana, Maine, Michigan, Mississippi, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Tennessee in the US.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dole Fresh Vegetables Announces Voluntary Recall of 'Dole Hearts Delight' Packaged Salads|first=Marty|last=Ordman|work=[[Food and Drug Administration]]|location=Silver Spring|accessdate=January 23, 2016|date=September 17, 2007|url=https://www.fda.gov/Safety/Recalls/ArchiveRecalls/2007/ucm112276.htm}}</ref>\n\n===2012 ''Salmonella'' recall===\nIn April 2012, random testing by the [[New York State Department of Health]] detected ''Salmonella'' bacteria in Dole's \"Seven Lettuces\" salad. The company issued a recall for the product, which had been distributed in Alabama, Florida, Illinois, Indiana, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, Mississippi, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Tennessee, Virginia and Wisconsin.<ref name=\"recalls\">{{cite news|work=[[Food Safety News]]|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2016/05/publishers-platform-will-the-justice-department-look-at-doles-history-of-recalls-and-outbreaks/|title=Will the Justice Department look at Dole's history of recalls and outbreaks?|date=May 2, 2016|accessdate=May 3, 2016|first=Bill|last=Marler|authorlink=William Marler}}</ref>\n\n===June 2012 ''Listeria'' recall===\nIn June 2012, random testing by the [[North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services]] detected ''[[Listeria monocytogenes]]'', the bacteria responsible for [[listeriosis]], in Dole's \"Marketside Leafy Romaine\" salad. The company issued a recall for the product, which had been distributed in Georgia, Kentucky, North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee and Virginia.<ref name=recalls/>\n\n===August 2012 ''Listeria'' recall===\nIn August 2012, random testing by the North Carolina Department of Agriculture detected ''Listeria monocytogenes'' in Dole's packaged \"Italian Blend\" salad. The company issued a recall for the product, which had been distributed in Alabama, Florida, North Carolina, South Carolina, Pennsylvania, Maryland, Mississippi and Virginia.<ref name=recalls/>\n\n===2014 ''Listeria'' recall===\nIn March 2014, random testing conducted by the Canadian Food Inspection Agency detected ''Listeria monocytogenes'' in Dole's packaged \"Italian Blend\" salad.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dole Brand Salad Recalled in Canada Due to Potential ''Listeria'' Contamination|date=March 13, 2014|work=[[Food Safety News]]|location=Seattle|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2014/03/dole-brand-salad-recalled-due-to-potential-listeria-contamination/#.UyN0DfldWAY|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> The company issued a recall for its Dole Italian Blend, Fresh Selections Italian Style Blend, Little Salad Bar Italian Salad, and Marketside Italian Style Salad products. The products had been distributed in Ontario, Quebec and New Brunswick in Canada, and Connecticut, Florida, Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Pennsylvania, South Carolina and Virginia in the US.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dole Expands Bagged Salad Recall to the U.S. Over ''Listeria'' Concerns|date=March 14, 2014|work=[[Food Safety News]]|location=Seattle|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2014/03/dole-expands-bagged-salad-recall-to-the-u-s-due-to-listeria/|accessdate=January 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2015 ''Salmonella'' recall===\nIn October 2015, random testing conducted by the [[Michigan Department of Agriculture and Rural Development]] detected ''[[Salmonella]]'' bacteria in a sample of Dole's packaged spinach salad. The company issued a recall for the product, which had been distributed to Connecticut, Indiana, Kentucky, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, Missouri, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Tennessee, and Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dole Fresh Vegetables Announces Precautionary Recall of Limited Number of Spinach Salads|date=October 13, 2015|work=[[Food and Drug Administration]]|location=Silver Spring|first=Bill|last=Goldfield}}</ref>\n\n===2016 Listeriosis outbreak===\nIn January 2016, packaged salads produced by Dole at its Springfield, Ohio, facility were linked to a multistate outbreak of listeriosis by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite news|title=Multistate Outbreak of Listeriosis Linked to Packaged Salads Produced at Springfield, Ohio Dole Processing Facility|date=January 22, 2016|work=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|location=Atlanta|url=https://www.cdc.gov/listeria/outbreaks/bagged-salads-01-16/index.html|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> The outbreak was first detected in July 2015 and led to the hospitalization of 12 people from Indiana, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey, New York, and Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite news|title=1 dead, 11 others hospitalized in listeria outbreak linked to Dole salads|first=Liz|last=Szabo|work=[[USA Today]]|location=Tysons Corner|date=January 22, 2016|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2016/01/22/deadly-listeria-outbreak-puts-12-people-hospital/79175942/|accessdate=January 23, 2016}}</ref> The victim from Michigan died as a result of the infection.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Listeria'' Outbreak Linked to Dole Salads From Ohio Facility|first1=Jesse|last1=Newman|first2=Ilan|last2=Brat|date=January 22, 2016|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|location=New York City|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/cdc-links-listeria-outbreak-to-dole-foods-ohio-facility-1453493700|accessdate=January 23, 2016}}</ref> A joint CDC and [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) investigation began in September 2015. In January 2016, testing of a Dole \"Field Greens\" packaged salad found the presence of ''Listeria monocytogenes'', the bacteria responsible for listeriosis.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Listeria'' Outbreak Linked to Dole's Packaged Salads|first=Alexandra|last=Sifferlin|date=January 22, 2016|url=http://time.com/4190945/listeria-outbreak-dole-packaged-salads/|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|location=New York City|accessdate=January 23, 2016}}</ref> On January 21, 2016, Dole suspended operations at the Springfield facility and began a recall of packaged salads produced there. The recall affected 23 states and 3 Canadian provinces, and involved salads packaged under the Dole, Fresh Selections, Simple Truth, Marketside, The Little Salad Bar, and President's Choice brand names.<ref>{{cite news|date=January 22, 2016|title=Food Recall Warning: Certain Dole brand pre-packaged chopped salads, salad blends and kits and leafy greens and certain PC Organics brand leafy greens recalled due to ''Listeria monocytogenes''|work=[[Canadian Food Inspection Agency]]|location=Ottawa|url=http://www.inspection.gc.ca/about-the-cfia/newsroom/food-recall-warnings/complete-listing/2016-01-22c/eng/1453522915084/1453522920123|accessdate=January 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dole Fresh Vegetables Announces a Voluntary Withdrawal of Salads Processed at its Springfield OH Processing Facility|work=Dole Food Company|location=Westlake Village|date=January 22, 2016|url=http://www.dole.com/en/about/withdrawal|accessdate=January 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, the [[United States Department of Justice|U.S. Department of Justice]] commenced a [[criminal investigation]] into Dole's role in the outbreak of listeriosis.<ref name=\"Beach\">{{cite news|work=[[Food Safety News]]|title=Dole knew of ''Listeria''; feds launch criminal investigation|first=Coral|last=Beach|date=April 29, 2016|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2016/04/fda-report-shows-dole-officials-knew-about-listeria-in-facility/#.VyOJBmNEz_Q|accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref> FDA inspection reports obtained by ''[[Food Safety News]]'' using the [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] demonstrated that in July 2014 Dole carried out swab tests of surfaces in the Springfield plant which returned positive results for ''Listeria'', but still did not cease production. Swab tests returned positive results \"five more times in 2014 and three times in late 2015\", but Dole continued production until January 2016.<ref name=Beach/> [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Rosa DeLauro]] said: \"News that Dole knew about a ''Listeria'' outbreak in their facility, yet continued to push contaminated salads onto the American consumer is an outrage. How could executives at Dole even consider putting products onto store shelves and into American homes when they knew for close to two years that there was a major public health issue? These executives must be held accountable for their unconscionable actions.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=DeLauro Demands That Dole Answer For Distributing Contaminated Salads That Killed Americans|work=[[United States House of Representatives]]|location=Washington, DC|date=April 29, 2016|url=http://delauro.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2288:delauro-demands-that-dole-answer-for-distributing-contaminated-salads-that-killed-americans&catid=2&Itemid=21#pq=9KHoVR|accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dole salad scandal spurs calls for stronger FDA|first=Coral|last=Beach|date=April 30, 2016|work=[[Food Safety News]]|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2016/04/125871/|accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and controversies==\n\n===Legal cases===\nIn 2001, Dole was involved in the suit [[Del Monte Fresh Produce Co. v. Dole Food Co.]] with Del Monte Fresh over the potential misappropriation of Del Monte's specially bred pineapple.\n\n===Hawaiian coup===\n{{main|Overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii}} \n[[James Dole]], who founded the [[Hawaiian Pineapple Company]], went to Hawaii in 1899, five years after his cousin (once removed), [[Sanford B. Dole]] had become first president of the  republic, following the overthrow of the Hawaiian monarchy.<ref name=\"Tsai\">{{citation |url= http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/150/sesq2dole |title=James Dole |first=Michael |last=Tsai  |work=[[The Honolulu Advertiser]] |publisher=[[Black Press]] |location=Honolulu, HI, USA |date=July 2, 2006 |accessdate=October 4, 2012}}</ref> Although his elder cousin was involved with the takeover of Hawaii, James himself was a teenager living in Massachusetts at the time of the coup.<ref name=\"Siddall\">{{cite book |title= Men of Hawaii: a biographical reference library, complete and authentic, of the men of note and substantial achievement in the Hawaiian Islands |publisher=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]] |location=Honolulu, HI, USA|year=1921 | editor-last=Siddall |editor-first=John William |volume=2 |series=The Story of Hawaii and its builders |id={{OCLC|80553001|32127632|16326675}} |lccn= 22017988 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4o8DAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA133 |page= 133 |accessdate=October 4, 2012}}</ref> However, the company's commercial activities would not have been possible without the later annexation of Hawaii to the US,<ref name=\"Okihiro\">{{Citation |last=Okihiro |first=Gary Y |author-link=Gary Okihiro |year=2009 |title=Pineapple culture : a history of the tropical and temperate zones |chapter=Hawaiian Pine |series=The California world history library |volume=10 |publisher=[[University of California Press]] |location=Berkeley, CA, USA |page=130 |isbn=9780520265905 |oclc=449860318}}</ref> which resulted in the removal of high import tariffs on Hawaiian products.<ref name=\"Overthrow\">\n{{cite book |title=Overthrow: America's Century of Regime Change from Hawaii to Iraq |title-link=Overthrow (book)  |last=Kinzer |first=Stephen |author-link=Kinzer, Stephen |publisher=[[Times Books]] |isbn=0-8050-7861-4 |date=2006-04-04 }}</ref>\nRemoval of tariffs through annexation was one of the goals of the 1894 coup plotters, though annexation did not occur until 1898.<ref name=\"Furnas\">{{Citation |last=Furnas |first=J. C. |author-link=J. C. Furnas |others=[[Institute of Pacific Relations]], American Council |year=1948 |origyear=1937 |title= Anatomy of paradise : Hawaii and the islands of the South Seas |chapter=Land of Makebelieve Come True |publisher=William Sloane Associates |location=New York, NY, USA |pages=173\u2013183 |id={{OCLC|577040553|183094599|8278107}} |chapter-url=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc1.b3378160?urlappend=%3Bseq=191 |accessdate=October 4, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.org/stream/anatomyofparadis012497mbp |archivedate=November 1, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Labor relations===\n[[File:004 Dole company, banana fruit sticker.jpg|thumb|220px|right|Dole banana fruit label]]\nThe [[banana industry]] has traditionally been dominated by a few large corporations, which employ [[low-wage work]]ers in [[developing countries]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Peter Chapman |title=Bananas: How the United Fruit Company Shaped the World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uQdHiU4lodAC&pg=PA21 |date=July 2009 |publisher=Canongate U.S. |isbn=978-1-84767-194-3 |page=21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= The Banana Trade War |work= Global Issues Blog |author= Anup Shah |date= January 3, 2010 |url= http://www.globalissues.org/article/63/the-banana-trade-war |accessdate= September 15, 2010 }}</ref> Dole was named as a defendant in a wrongful death lawsuit filed on behalf of 73 heirs of victims of paramilitary violence in Colombia.<ref>{{cite web |title= Juana Perez 1-51/Juan Perez 5E-50 v. Dole Food Company, Inc. |publisher= International Rights Advocates |work= Cases |date= April 2009 |url= http://www.iradvocates.org/dolecase.html |accessdate= 2010-01-20 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100523100708/http://www.iradvocates.org/dolecase.html |archivedate= 2010-05-23 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, [[Nicaragua]]n [[banana plantation|plantation]] workers, represented by [[Los Angeles]]-based [[personal injury]] [[lawyer]] [[Juan Dominguez (lawyer)|Juan Dominguez]], sued Dole and [[Dow Chemical Company]], claiming the use of illegal pesticides such as the now banned [[1,2-Dibromo-3-chloropropane|Nemagon]] (containing DBCP) had made them [[Infertility|sterile]]. The pesticide was not banned in Nicaragua until after Dole ceased its operations within the country. The suit and two others were subsequently thrown out by California courts after it was concluded that \u201c[c]ontrary to their sworn testimony, most of the plaintiffs never worked on Dole-affiliated banana farms and none were involved in the DBCP application process,\u201d while similar lawsuits were filed in U.S. and Nicaraguan courts.<ref name=\"bloomberg.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109&sid=aS5ED.ApmVPk | work=Bloomberg | title=Dole Uses Judge Attack in Banana Case to Undo $2 Billion Awards | date=June 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nA lawyer for the Nicaraguans, Steve Condie, however, alleged that some of the witnesses had been paid by Dole to give testimony that the claims were fraudulent.  The witnesses' identities were kept secret so that the plaintiffs' lawyers could not interview them.<ref name=\"bloomberg.com\"/>\n\nSwedish film director [[Fredrik Gertten]] made a documentary film about Dominguez and the alleged banana workers. The movie ''[[Bananas!*]]'' premiered in the 2009 [[Los Angeles Film Festival]]. Dole said they had serious concerns about the film's accuracy and they urged festival officials to \"immediately cease and desist\" their sponsorship of the film.<ref name=\"Edelman\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bananasthemovie.com/wp-content/uploads/resources/letter_from_dole_may8_09.pdf |title=Letter from Dole, May 8, 2009 |first=Scott A.|last=Edelman |work=bananasthemovie.com |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bananasthemovie.com/interview-with-director-fredrik-gertten/ |title=Interview with director Fredrik Gertten &#124; BANANAS!* |publisher=Bananasthemovie.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://svt.se/2.33782/1.1591791/bananas_far_inte_tavla_pa_festival |title=Bananas f\u00e5r inte t\u00e4vla p\u00e5 festival \u2013 Regionala nyheter |publisher=svt.se |accessdate=2012-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006015213/http://www.svt.se/2.33782/1.1591791/bananas_far_inte_tavla_pa_festival |archivedate=2012-10-06 }}</ref><ref name=\"bananasthemovie_com-_article\">{{cite web|title=About the film \u2013 BANANAS!*|url=http://www.bananasthemovie.com/about-the-film/#article}} 11 June 2009 \u2013 bananasthemovie.com</ref> The festival officials allowed the film to be screened, but it was not allowed to compete for placement in the competition. In addition, festival officials distributed information before the film's screening that indicated Dole believed the film to be factually inaccurate.\n\nAlthough the film was screened with a disclaimer from the festival, Gertten was subsequently sued for defamation by Dole.<ref name=\"Deutcsh\">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/businesstechnology/2009346592_apusdolebananaworkers.html |title=Dole sues 'Bananas!' filmmaker, alleges defamation |first=Linda |last=Deutcsh |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=July 9, 2009 |publisher=[[The Seattle Times Company]] |location=Seattle, WA, USA |accessdate=October 4, 2012}}</ref> The lawsuit was dropped on October 15, 2009, and in November 2010 a court in Los Angeles found in favour of the movie crew making it possible to release the movie in the US, and ordering Dole to pay SEK 1.4 million (roughly US$200,000) to the filmmakers.<ref name=\"Mlik\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/film-tv/-filmen-bananas-vann-mot-dole |title=Filmen \"Bananas\" vann mot Dole |trans-title=The film \"Bananas\" won against Dole |language=Swedish |first=Nora |last=Mlik |publisher=Dn.se |location=Stockholm, Sweden |accessdate=October 6, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116171719/http://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/film-tv/-filmen-bananas-vann-mot-dole |archivedate=January 16, 2013 }} {{Google translation|en|sv|http://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/film-tv/-filmen-bananas-vann-mot-dole|Google  machine translation of this article}}</ref>\n\nGertten's sequel ''[[Big Boys Gone Bananas!*]]'' documents Dole's reactions to ''Bananas!*''.\n\nThe Nicaraguan DBCP awards against Dole were overturned in July 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title= Judge throws out verdict awarding millions to Dole workers |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |author= Victoria Kim |date= July 16, 2010 |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/16/local/la-me-dole-20100716  |accessdate= September 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013 [[Oxfam]] demanded Dole remove its \"Ethical Choice\" labels from its bananas in New Zealand until it improved treatment of its workers in [[the Philippines]], but Dole said Oxfam was trying to \"destroy the Dole brand\" in favour of other suppliers.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Dole-bananas-not-ethical---Oxfam/tabid/1160/articleID/299404/Default.aspx |work=3 News NZ |title= Dole bananas not ethical \u2013 Oxfam| date=May 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn Oct 2018 Myanmar Government blacklisted Thailand subsidiary of Dole after investigation found that one of its factory in Thailand exploited Myanmar migrant workers by demanding payments for visas, medical check-ups and work permit fees. Myanmar migrant workers are also prevented from taking paid annual leave. About 130 Myanmar migrants who took annual leaves were prevented from returning to work and got fired instead.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.mmtimes.com/news/govt-blacklists-dole-thailand-over-labour-dispute.html |work=MyanmarTimes MM |title= Govt blacklists Dole-Thailand over labour dispute| date=Oct 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Labeling of genetically engineered foods in California===\nIn 2012, Dole Packaged Foods contributed $171,261 to a $46 million political campaign known as \"The Coalition Against The Costly Food Labeling Proposition, sponsored by Farmers and Food Producers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcet.org/news/ballotbrief/elections2012/propositions/prop-37-funding-genetically-engineered-food.html |title=Who's Funding Prop 37, Labeling for Genetically Engineered Foods? &#124; Propositions &#124; Elections 2012 |publisher=KCET.org |date= |accessdate=2015-06-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n; Media\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YkI3zkQ4WBo|title=Why The Banana Business Of Chiquita And Dole Is At Risk|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2019-04-21}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Portal|Hawaii|Los Angeles|Food|Companies}}\n* {{Official website|www.dole.com}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120214183130/http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/10/10303.html Yahoo! - Dole Food Company, Inc. Company Profile]\n\n{{Dole Food Company}}\n{{Pineapples}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Dole Food Company| ]]\n[[Category:Agriculture companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Food manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Multinational food companies]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the United States]]\n[[Category:Pineapple production]]\n[[Category:Business in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Westlake Village, California]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1851]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1851]]\n[[Category:1851 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Banana production]]\n[[Category:Fruit production]]\n[[Category:2013 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Dole family]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name                = Dole Food Company, Inc.\n| logo                = Dole Logo.svg\n| type                = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| genre               = \n| foundation          = <!-- this parameter modifies \"Founded\" -->{{start date and age|1851|6|2}}<ref name=\"dole\">[http://www.dole.com/CompanyInfo/About/History.jsp Dole: Company History] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117163821/http://www.dole.com/CompanyInfo/About/History.jsp |date=November 17, 2007 }} (Retrieved November 29, 2007)</ref><br>[[Kingdom of Hawaii]]\n| founder             = [[Samuel Northrup Castle]] <br> [[Amos Starr Cooke]]\n| location_city       = [[Westlake Village, California|Westlake Village]], [[California]]\n| location_country    = U.S.\n| location            = <!-- this parameter modifies \"Headquarters\" -->\n| origins             = \n| key_people          = [[David H. Murdock]]<br>[[Chairman]]<br>[[Carl McCann]]<br>[[Deputy Chairman]]<br>[[Johan Lind\u00e9n]]<br>[[President, COO, CEO]]\n| industry            = [[Agribusiness]]\n| products            = [[Fruit]]<br>[[Vegetables]]<br>Other food products\n| services            = \n| revenue             = [[United States dollar|US$]]4.5 billion (2016)<ref name=\"hoovers\">\n[http://www.hoovers.com/dole-food/--ID__10303--/free-co-factsheet.xhtml Hoover's: Dole Food Company, Inc. Factsheet] (Retrieved April 2, 2012)</ref>\n| operating_income    = \n| net_income          = $38.4 million (2011)<ref name=\"hoovers\"/>\n| num_employees       = 34,500 (2011)<ref name=\"busweek\">{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=259280 |title=Dole Food Company Inc.: Private Company Information \u2013 Businessweek |publisher=Investing.businessweek.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref>\n| parent              = \n| divisions           = \n| subsid              = \n| owner               = \n| slogan              = \n| homepage            = {{URL|www.dole.com}}\n| dissolved           = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Dole Food Company, Inc.''' is an [[United States|American]] [[agricultural]] [[multinational corporation]] headquartered in [[Westlake Village, California]]. The company is the largest [[food industry|producer]] of [[fruit]] and [[vegetables]] in the world, operating with 74,300 full-time and seasonal employees who are responsible for over 300 products in 90 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/10/10303.html |title=Dole Food Company, Inc. Company Profile \u2013 Yahoo! Finance |publisher=Biz.yahoo.com |date=2012-09-25 |accessdate=2012-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116165632/http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/10/10303.html |archivedate=2013-01-16 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoovers.com/company/Dole_Food_Company_Inc/rfyfyi-1.html |title=&#124; Company Profile from Hoover's |publisher=Hoovers.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref> Dole markets such food items as [[bananas]], [[pineapples]], [[grapes]], [[strawberries]], salads, and other fresh and frozen fruits and juices. Dole owns a shipping line, Dole Ocean Cargo Express.\n\nDole's chairman founded the [[Dole Nutrition Institute]], a nutritional research and education foundation.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:DolePineapplePlantation.jpg|thumb|left|Dole Plantation on [[Oahu, Hawaii]].]]\nThe company traces its origin to the 1851 establishment of [[Castle & Cooke]] by missionaries [[Samuel Northrup Castle]] and [[Amos Starr Cooke]]. Castle & Cooke rapidly became one of the largest companies in Hawaii, investing in shipping, railroad construction, sugar production and seafood packing. The other half of Dole's corporate heritage, the '''Hawaiian Pineapple Company''', was founded in 1901 by [[James Dole]], who opened his first pineapple plantation in the central plateau of the Hawaiian island of [[Oahu]]. [[Sanford Dole]], the cousin of James, had been president of the [[Republic of Hawaii]] from 1894 after the [[overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii]] (her last monarch, [[Liliuokalani|Queen Lili{{okina}}uokalani]]), and first governor of the [[Territory of Hawaii]] until 1903.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://archives1.dags.hawaii.gov/gsdl/collect/governme/index/assoc/HASHb5a9/8f7a506f.dir/Dole,%20Sanford%20Ballard.jpg |title= Dole, Sanford Ballard office record |work= state archives digital collections |publisher= state of Hawaii |accessdate= 2010-01-20 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120306203149/http://archives1.dags.hawaii.gov/gsdl/collect/governme/index/assoc/HASHb5a9/8f7a506f.dir/Dole%2C%20Sanford%20Ballard.jpg |archivedate= 2012-03-06 }}</ref>\nThe annexation of Hawaii to the United States made selling agricultural products to the mainland much more profitable, since they would never be subject to import [[tariff]]s.\n\nIn 1932, Castle & Cooke purchased a 21% interest in the Hawaiian Pineapple Company. In the 1960s, Castle & Cooke acquired the remainder of the Hawaiian Pineapple Company and the [[Standard Fruit Company]]. In 1976, it acquired Bud Antle Inc., a California-based lettuce and celery farmer; it was renamed Dole Fresh Vegetables in 1989. The company was renamed \"The Dole Food Company, Inc\" in 1991. Castle & Cooke Inc, a [[real estate]] company, was spun off in 1995; it is currently operating as a subsidiary of Flexi-Van Leasing, Inc. Dole's [[Waialua Sugar Mill]] closed in 1996.<ref>{{Cite news| last = Star-Bulletin| first = Russ Lynch| title = Waialua closing the book on Oahu's sugar industry \u2013 Today is the last day of harvesting and by Saturday the shutdown will be complete| work = Honolulu Star-Bulletin (HI)| accessdate = 2018-04-22| date = 1996-10-02| url = http://infoweb.newsbank.com/resources/doc/nb/news/1296CDE56F67D958?p=NewsBank|via=[[NewsBank]]}}</ref> Dole acquired Coastal Berry in 2004 and SunnyRidge Farms in 2011 to enter the berry business.<ref>[http://vegetablegrowersnews.com/news/dole-food-acquires-coastal-berry/ Dole Food Acquires Coastal Berry]</ref><ref>[http://www.growingproduce.com/uncategorized/dole-acquires-sunnyridge-farm/ Dole Acquires SunnyRidge Farm]</ref>\n\n[[File:Dole freighter in San Juan, Puerto Rico.jpg|thumb|200px|Dole freighter sailing out of [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]]]]\nIt was then the third largest producer and U.S. importer of bananas. Dole and [[Chiquita]] remain the top two U.S. banana companies as of 2011. In 2011, the company reported $7.2 billion in annual [[revenue]].<ref name=\"hoovers\"/>\n\nDole operates plantations throughout [[Central America|Central]] and [[South America]], and in the [[Asia-Pacific]] region, with plantations in the [[Philippines]] and two packing plants in [[Thailand]], [[Hua Hin]] and [[Chumphon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dole.co.th/en/#contact-us |title=Locations of Dole Food Company in Thailand |year=2012 |publisher=Dole Food Company |accessdate=9 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930002306/http://www.dole.co.th/en#contact-us |archive-date=30 September 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAs part of a major restructuring in 2012, Dole agreed to sell its worldwide packaged foods and Asian fresh produce businesses to Japanese trading house [[Itochu]] for $1.7 billion in cash. The transaction paid down a large amount of Dole's debt and refocused the company's business on fresh fruit and vegetables.<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan's Itochu to buy Dole Food businesses for $1.7 billion|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/09/18/us-dolefood-itochu-idUSBRE88H01L20120918|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> The businesses acquired by Itochu continue to use the Dole brand and are owned by Dole International Holdings, a Tokyo-based subsidiary of Itochu.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dole Business|url=http://www.itochu.co.jp/en/business/food/project/10/|publisher=Itochu Corporation|accessdate=2 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908001600/http://www.itochu.co.jp/en/business/food/project/10/|archivedate=8 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Dole announced that CEO David Murdock would acquire the outstanding stock of the company for $1.2 billion.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323585604579008502351303672 | title=Dole Food Agrees to $1.2 Billion Buyout Offer | work=The Wall Street Journal | date=August 12, 2013 | accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref> The sale closed in October 2013, but was challenged by shareholders who argued that the company was undervalued, based in part on underestimated cost savings from the 2012 sale of the Asia business. In 2015, the [[Delaware Chancery Court]] awarded $148 million in damages to the former shareholders, on the grounds that Murdock and chief operating officer C. Michael Carter had misled shareholders regarding the finances of the company.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hoffman|first1=Liz|title=Dole Executives Ordered to Pay $148 Million in Buyout Lawsuit|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/dole-executives-ordered-to-pay-148-million-in-buyout-lawsuit-1440686542|accessdate=2 September 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=27 August 2015}}</ref> Dole, which had moved its corporate registration from Hawaii to Delaware in 2001, became an outspoken critic of Delaware corporate law as a result of this litigation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hoffman|first1=Liz|title=Dole and Other Companies Sour on Delaware as Corporate Haven|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/dole-and-other-companies-sour-on-delaware-as-corporate-haven-1438569507|accessdate=2 September 2015|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=2 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nDole is a vertically integrated producer, owning plantations in Central America.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wang|first1=Dan|title=Meet Dole, the World's Full-Stack Banana Company|url=https://www.flexport.com/blog/why-dole-owns-container-ships/|publisher=Flexport|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref>  It operates a fleet of 19 container ships<ref>{{cite web|title=Vessels|url=http://www.doleoceancargo.com/vessels.html|publisher=Dole Ocean Cargo|accessdate=5 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206002505/http://www.doleoceancargo.com/vessels.html|archive-date=6 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> that are specially equipped to support refrigerated containers and have their own cranes instead of relying on port infrastructure.\n\n===Management===\nIn April 2017, Johan Linden was named [[chief executive officer]], in addition to his role as President,<ref>{{cite web|title=Executive Profile: Johan Linden, Chief Executive Officer and President, Dole Food Company, Inc.|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=290561769&privcapId=259280&previousCapId=259280&previousTitle=Dole%20Food%20Company%20Inc.|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=31 January 2018|date=January 2018}}</ref> and Johan Malmavist was [[chief financial officer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Ranking of America's Largest Private Companies: Dole Food|url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/dole-food/|work=Forbes|accessdate=31 January 2018|date=2018}}</ref>\n\n===Products===\n[[File:Dolejf2103.JPG|thumb|220px|right|Fresh ripe Dole pineapples ([[Philippines]])]]\nIncluding the original [[pineapple]], Dole distributes fresh plant foods in the forms of  whole fruits, whole vegetables,  berries, and fresh-cut vegetables. \nPackaged products include fruit bowls, fruit bowls in gel, fruit in plastic jars, fruit parfaits, fruit crisps, dates, raisins, and canned fruits. \nFrozen products include berries, tropical fruits, and fruit bars.\nJuices are sold chilled, frozen, or canned.\nSalad products include greens, salad kits, and shreds.<ref>{{cite web |title= All About Dole Products |work= official web site |publisher= Dole Food, Inc |url= http://www.dole.com/EatRightLanding/EatRtProductIndex/tabid/892/Default.aspx |accessdate= September 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 Dole bought several growers in [[Colombia]] and became the largest distributor of fresh-cut flowers in the US. However, by 2008 the flower business was losing money, and it was bought in January 2009 by a group of private investors.\n\n===Corporate headquarters===\nIn 1994, Dole announced that it would finalize its plans to build its world headquarters on a {{convert|30|acre|m2|adj=on}} site owned by the company, located north of the [[Ventura Freeway]] in [[Westlake Village, California|Westlake Village]], California. The decision had been delayed by groundwater contamination tests and reviewing of possible site plan revisions. Having submitted its plans for final approval by the Westlake Village City Council on February 9, 1994,<ref>{{cite news |title= Dole gets ready to turn first shovel of headquarters dirt: plans are set to go to Westlake Village City Council |work= [[Los Angeles Business Journal]] |date= January 31, 1994 |url= http://www.allbusiness.com/north-america/united-states-california-metro-areas/426968-1.html |accessdate= September 15, 2010 }}</ref> Dole completed construction and opened its new world headquarters building in May 1999.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[Image:Pineapple maze 1.JPG|thumb|Dole Plantation Pineapple Maze]]\n\nThe [[Guinness Book of World Records]] (2007) lists the pineapple maze at the Dole Plantation in [[Oahu, Hawaii|Honolulu, Hawaii]] as the world's largest [[maze]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dole-plantation.com/Maze/maze.aspx |title=Dole Plantation \u2013 Hawaii's Complete Pineapple Experience \u2013 Maze |accessdate=2008-02-14 |publisher=Dole Plantation, Inc. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080121014452/http://www.dole-plantation.com/Maze/maze.aspx |archivedate=2008-01-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Dole Nutrition Institute]] (DNI) was founded by David H. Murdock in 2003 to \"Feed the World with Knowledge\" through research and education regarding the health benefits of a plant-based diet.\n\n==Mascot==\n[[File:Dole Mascots (41848912380) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Bobby Banana and Pinellopy Pineapple in San Diego in 2018]]\n'''Bobby Banana''' is a [[mascot]] of Dole Food Company and the leader of the SuperKids (children who regularly eat five to nine fruits and vegetables every day).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dole.com/WhatsASuperkid/tabid/824/Default.aspx |title=WhatsASuperkid |publisher=Dole |date= |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref>  He is an [[anthropomorphism|anthropomorphic]] [[banana]] who appears in Dole comics and games for children, along with friends Courtney Cauliflower, Mia Mango, Pinellopy Pineapple, and Gavin Grape, all of whom are also anthropomorphic fruits and vegetables.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dole.com/DoleFlashHomePage/tabid/972/Default.aspx#/superkids/ |title=Homepage |publisher=Dole |date=2010-06-21 |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985 and 1986, the Dole banana was featured as the official banana of the Pittsburg State University (KS) Gorillas' athletic programs.  The project was the brainchild of then Pitt State radiosports play-by-play voice Scott Burton.  The introduction of the Dole banana as the official banana of the Gorillas delighted then Athletic Director David Suenram and Pittsburg State University sports fans alike.  The head football coach at the time of the promotion was Dennis Franchione.  Dole provided company trinkets for fan giveaways and the popularity of the Dole banana thrived in southeast Kansas and southwest Missouri (Joplin) during the promotion's two-year run.\n\n==Advertising==\n\nFor a number of years, the [[country music]] artist [[Kenny Rogers]] advertised Dole's products on television. He would often be accompanied by his then wife, Marianne. Dole also sponsored several of Rogers' concert tours.\n\n==Food safety==\n\n===2005 ''E. coli'' outbreak===\nIn 2005, 23 people in [[Minnesota]] were sickened with [[E. coli O157:H7|''E. coli'' O157:H7]]. The source of the [[bacteria]] was found to be Dole brand bagged lettuce.<ref name=\"Murphey\">{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090208032833/http://www.producenews.com/storydetail.cfm?ID=5449 |archivedate=February 8, 2009 |url=http://www.producenews.com/storydetail.cfm?ID=5449 |title=Minnesota finds ''E. coli'' in lettuce bags |first=Joan |last=Murphy |location=Oradell, NJ, USA |work=The Produce News |issn=0032-969X|oclc=4109334|date=October 17, 2005 |accessdate=October 5, 2012|via=[[Wayback Machine]]}}</ref>\n\n===2006 ''E. coli'' outbreak===\n{{main|2006 North American E. coli O157:H7 outbreak in spinach}}\nIn 2006, an ''E. coli'' outbreak that caused over 200 people to become ill and killed 3 more was linked to bagged [[spinach]] sold by Dole. The spinach was processed by Natural Selection Foods in [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.about-ecoli.com/ecoli_outbreaks/news/e-coli-found-in-water-wild-pig-near-california-spinach-farm/ |title=''E. coli'' Food Poisoning |publisher=About-ecoli.com |date=2006-10-27 |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref>\n\n===2007 ''E. coli'' recall===\nIn September 2007, random testing conducted by the [[Canadian Food Inspection Agency]] detected ''E. coli'' O157:H7 bacteria in Dole's \"Hearts Delight\" packaged salad. The company issued a recall for the product, which had been distributed in Ontario, Quebec, New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, and Prince Edward Island in Canada, and in Illinois, Indiana, Maine, Michigan, Mississippi, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Tennessee in the US.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dole Fresh Vegetables Announces Voluntary Recall of 'Dole Hearts Delight' Packaged Salads|first=Marty|last=Ordman|work=[[Food and Drug Administration]]|location=Silver Spring|accessdate=January 23, 2016|date=September 17, 2007|url=https://www.fda.gov/Safety/Recalls/ArchiveRecalls/2007/ucm112276.htm}}</ref>\n\n===2012 ''Salmonella'' recall===\nIn April 2012, random testing by the [[New York State Department of Health]] detected ''Salmonella'' bacteria in Dole's \"Seven Lettuces\" salad. The company issued a recall for the product, which had been distributed in Alabama, Florida, Illinois, Indiana, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, Mississippi, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Tennessee, Virginia and Wisconsin.<ref name=\"recalls\">{{cite news|work=[[Food Safety News]]|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2016/05/publishers-platform-will-the-justice-department-look-at-doles-history-of-recalls-and-outbreaks/|title=Will the Justice Department look at Dole's history of recalls and outbreaks?|date=May 2, 2016|accessdate=May 3, 2016|first=Bill|last=Marler|authorlink=William Marler}}</ref>\n\n===June 2012 ''Listeria'' recall===\nIn June 2012, random testing by the [[North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services]] detected ''[[Listeria monocytogenes]]'', the bacteria responsible for [[listeriosis]], in Dole's \"Marketside Leafy Romaine\" salad. The company issued a recall for the product, which had been distributed in Georgia, Kentucky, North Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee and Virginia.<ref name=recalls/>\n\n===August 2012 ''Listeria'' recall===\nIn August 2012, random testing by the North Carolina Department of Agriculture detected ''Listeria monocytogenes'' in Dole's packaged \"Italian Blend\" salad. The company issued a recall for the product, which had been distributed in Alabama, Florida, North Carolina, South Carolina, Pennsylvania, Maryland, Mississippi and Virginia.<ref name=recalls/>\n\n===2014 ''Listeria'' recall===\nIn March 2014, random testing conducted by the Canadian Food Inspection Agency detected ''Listeria monocytogenes'' in Dole's packaged \"Italian Blend\" salad.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dole Brand Salad Recalled in Canada Due to Potential ''Listeria'' Contamination|date=March 13, 2014|work=[[Food Safety News]]|location=Seattle|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2014/03/dole-brand-salad-recalled-due-to-potential-listeria-contamination/#.UyN0DfldWAY|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref> The company issued a recall for its Dole Italian Blend, Fresh Selections Italian Style Blend, Little Salad Bar Italian Salad, and Marketside Italian Style Salad products. The products had been distributed in Ontario, Quebec and New Brunswick in Canada, and Connecticut, Florida, Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Pennsylvania, South Carolina and Virginia in the US.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dole Expands Bagged Salad Recall to the U.S. Over ''Listeria'' Concerns|date=March 14, 2014|work=[[Food Safety News]]|location=Seattle|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2014/03/dole-expands-bagged-salad-recall-to-the-u-s-due-to-listeria/|accessdate=January 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2015 ''Salmonella'' recall===\nIn October 2015, random testing conducted by the [[Michigan Department of Agriculture and Rural Development]] detected ''[[Salmonella]]'' bacteria in a sample of Dole's packaged spinach salad. The company issued a recall for the product, which had been distributed to Connecticut, Indiana, Kentucky, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, Missouri, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Tennessee, and Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dole Fresh Vegetables Announces Precautionary Recall of Limited Number of Spinach Salads|date=October 13, 2015|work=[[Food and Drug Administration]]|location=Silver Spring|first=Bill|last=Goldfield}}</ref>\n\n===2016 Listeriosis outbreak===\nIn January 2016, packaged salads produced by Dole at its Springfield, Ohio, facility were linked to a multistate outbreak of listeriosis by the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC).<ref>{{cite news|title=Multistate Outbreak of Listeriosis Linked to Packaged Salads Produced at Springfield, Ohio Dole Processing Facility|date=January 22, 2016|work=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]]|location=Atlanta|url=https://www.cdc.gov/listeria/outbreaks/bagged-salads-01-16/index.html|accessdate=January 23, 2013}}</ref> The outbreak was first detected in July 2015 and led to the hospitalization of 12 people from Indiana, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey, New York, and Pennsylvania.<ref>{{cite news|title=1 dead, 11 others hospitalized in listeria outbreak linked to Dole salads|first=Liz|last=Szabo|work=[[USA Today]]|location=Tysons Corner|date=January 22, 2016|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2016/01/22/deadly-listeria-outbreak-puts-12-people-hospital/79175942/|accessdate=January 23, 2016}}</ref> The victim from Michigan died as a result of the infection.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Listeria'' Outbreak Linked to Dole Salads From Ohio Facility|first1=Jesse|last1=Newman|first2=Ilan|last2=Brat|date=January 22, 2016|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|location=New York City|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/cdc-links-listeria-outbreak-to-dole-foods-ohio-facility-1453493700|accessdate=January 23, 2016}}</ref> A joint CDC and [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) investigation began in September 2015. In January 2016, testing of a Dole \"Field Greens\" packaged salad found the presence of ''Listeria monocytogenes'', the bacteria responsible for listeriosis.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Listeria'' Outbreak Linked to Dole's Packaged Salads|first=Alexandra|last=Sifferlin|date=January 22, 2016|url=http://time.com/4190945/listeria-outbreak-dole-packaged-salads/|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|location=New York City|accessdate=January 23, 2016}}</ref> On January 21, 2016, Dole suspended operations at the Springfield facility and began a recall of packaged salads produced there. The recall affected 23 states and 3 Canadian provinces, and involved salads packaged under the Dole, Fresh Selections, Simple Truth, Marketside, The Little Salad Bar, and President's Choice brand names.<ref>{{cite news|date=January 22, 2016|title=Food Recall Warning: Certain Dole brand pre-packaged chopped salads, salad blends and kits and leafy greens and certain PC Organics brand leafy greens recalled due to ''Listeria monocytogenes''|work=[[Canadian Food Inspection Agency]]|location=Ottawa|url=http://www.inspection.gc.ca/about-the-cfia/newsroom/food-recall-warnings/complete-listing/2016-01-22c/eng/1453522915084/1453522920123|accessdate=January 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dole Fresh Vegetables Announces a Voluntary Withdrawal of Salads Processed at its Springfield OH Processing Facility|work=Dole Food Company|location=Westlake Village|date=January 22, 2016|url=http://www.dole.com/en/about/withdrawal|accessdate=January 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, the [[United States Department of Justice|U.S. Department of Justice]] commenced a [[criminal investigation]] into Dole's role in the outbreak of listeriosis.<ref name=\"Beach\">{{cite news|work=[[Food Safety News]]|title=Dole knew of ''Listeria''; feds launch criminal investigation|first=Coral|last=Beach|date=April 29, 2016|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2016/04/fda-report-shows-dole-officials-knew-about-listeria-in-facility/#.VyOJBmNEz_Q|accessdate=April 30, 2016}}</ref> FDA inspection reports obtained by ''[[Food Safety News]]'' using the [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] demonstrated that in July 2014 Dole carried out swab tests of surfaces in the Springfield plant which returned positive results for ''Listeria'', but still did not cease production. Swab tests returned positive results \"five more times in 2014 and three times in late 2015\", but Dole continued production until January 2016.<ref name=Beach/> [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Rosa DeLauro]] said: \"News that Dole knew about a ''Listeria'' outbreak in their facility, yet continued to push contaminated salads onto the American consumer is an outrage. How could executives at Dole even consider putting products onto store shelves and into American homes when they knew for close to two years that there was a major public health issue? These executives must be held accountable for their unconscionable actions.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=DeLauro Demands That Dole Answer For Distributing Contaminated Salads That Killed Americans|work=[[United States House of Representatives]]|location=Washington, DC|date=April 29, 2016|url=http://delauro.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2288:delauro-demands-that-dole-answer-for-distributing-contaminated-salads-that-killed-americans&catid=2&Itemid=21#pq=9KHoVR|accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dole salad scandal spurs calls for stronger FDA|first=Coral|last=Beach|date=April 30, 2016|work=[[Food Safety News]]|url=http://www.foodsafetynews.com/2016/04/125871/|accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism and controversies==\n\n===Legal cases===\nIn 2001, Dole was involved in the suit [[Del Monte Fresh Produce Co. v. Dole Food Co.]] with Del Monte Fresh over the potential misappropriation of Del Monte's specially bred pineapple.\n\n===Hawaiian coup===\n{{main|Overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawaii}} \n[[James Dole]], who founded the [[Hawaiian Pineapple Company]], went to Hawaii in 1899, five years after his cousin (once removed), [[Sanford B. Dole]] had become first president of the  republic, following the overthrow of the Hawaiian monarchy.<ref name=\"Tsai\">{{citation |url= http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/150/sesq2dole |title=James Dole |first=Michael |last=Tsai  |work=[[The Honolulu Advertiser]] |publisher=[[Black Press]] |location=Honolulu, HI, USA |date=July 2, 2006 |accessdate=October 4, 2012}}</ref> Although his elder cousin was involved with the takeover of Hawaii, James himself was a teenager living in Massachusetts at the time of the coup.<ref name=\"Siddall\">{{cite book |title= Men of Hawaii: a biographical reference library, complete and authentic, of the men of note and substantial achievement in the Hawaiian Islands |publisher=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]] |location=Honolulu, HI, USA|year=1921 | editor-last=Siddall |editor-first=John William |volume=2 |series=The Story of Hawaii and its builders |id={{OCLC|80553001|32127632|16326675}} |lccn= 22017988 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4o8DAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA133 |page= 133 |accessdate=October 4, 2012}}</ref> However, the company's commercial activities would not have been possible without the later annexation of Hawaii to the US,<ref name=\"Okihiro\">{{Citation |last=Okihiro |first=Gary Y |author-link=Gary Okihiro |year=2009 |title=Pineapple culture : a history of the tropical and temperate zones |chapter=Hawaiian Pine |series=The California world history library |volume=10 |publisher=[[University of California Press]] |location=Berkeley, CA, USA |page=130 |isbn=9780520265905 |oclc=449860318}}</ref> which resulted in the removal of high import tariffs on Hawaiian products.<ref name=\"Overthrow\">\n{{cite book |title=Overthrow: America's Century of Regime Change from Hawaii to Iraq |title-link=Overthrow (book)  |last=Kinzer |first=Stephen |author-link=Kinzer, Stephen |publisher=[[Times Books]] |isbn=0-8050-7861-4 |date=2006-04-04 }}</ref>\nRemoval of tariffs through annexation was one of the goals of the 1894 coup plotters, though annexation did not occur until 1898.<ref name=\"Furnas\">{{Citation |last=Furnas |first=J. C. |author-link=J. C. Furnas |others=[[Institute of Pacific Relations]], American Council |year=1948 |origyear=1937 |title= Anatomy of paradise : Hawaii and the islands of the South Seas |chapter=Land of Makebelieve Come True |publisher=William Sloane Associates |location=New York, NY, USA |pages=173\u2013183 |id={{OCLC|577040553|183094599|8278107}} |chapter-url=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/uc1.b3378160?urlappend=%3Bseq=191 |accessdate=October 4, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.org/stream/anatomyofparadis012497mbp |archivedate=November 1, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Labor relations===\n[[File:004 Dole company, banana fruit sticker.jpg|thumb|220px|right|Dole banana fruit label]]\nThe [[banana industry]] has traditionally been dominated by a few large corporations, which employ [[low-wage work]]ers in [[developing countries]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Peter Chapman |title=Bananas: How the United Fruit Company Shaped the World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uQdHiU4lodAC&pg=PA21 |date=July 2009 |publisher=Canongate U.S. |isbn=978-1-84767-194-3 |page=21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= The Banana Trade War |work= Global Issues Blog |author= Anup Shah |date= January 3, 2010 |url= http://www.globalissues.org/article/63/the-banana-trade-war |accessdate= September 15, 2010 }}</ref> Dole was named as a defendant in a wrongful death lawsuit filed on behalf of 73 heirs of victims of paramilitary violence in Colombia.<ref>{{cite web |title= Juana Perez 1-51/Juan Perez 5E-50 v. Dole Food Company, Inc. |publisher= International Rights Advocates |work= Cases |date= April 2009 |url= http://www.iradvocates.org/dolecase.html |accessdate= 2010-01-20 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100523100708/http://www.iradvocates.org/dolecase.html |archivedate= 2010-05-23 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, [[Nicaragua]]n [[banana plantation|plantation]] workers, represented by [[Los Angeles]]-based [[personal injury]] [[lawyer]] [[Juan Dominguez (lawyer)|Juan Dominguez]], sued Dole and [[Dow Chemical Company]], claiming the use of illegal pesticides such as the now banned [[1,2-Dibromo-3-chloropropane|Nemagon]] (containing DBCP) had made them [[Infertility|sterile]]. The pesticide was not banned in Nicaragua until after Dole ceased its operations within the country. The suit and two others were subsequently thrown out by California courts after it was concluded that \u201c[c]ontrary to their sworn testimony, most of the plaintiffs never worked on Dole-affiliated banana farms and none were involved in the DBCP application process,\u201d while similar lawsuits were filed in U.S. and Nicaraguan courts.<ref name=\"bloomberg.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601109&sid=aS5ED.ApmVPk | work=Bloomberg | title=Dole Uses Judge Attack in Banana Case to Undo $2 Billion Awards | date=June 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\nA lawyer for the Nicaraguans, Steve Condie, however, alleged that some of the witnesses had been paid by Dole to give testimony that the claims were fraudulent.  The witnesses' identities were kept secret so that the plaintiffs' lawyers could not interview them.<ref name=\"bloomberg.com\"/>\n\nSwedish film director [[Fredrik Gertten]] made a documentary film about Dominguez and the alleged banana workers. The movie ''[[Bananas!*]]'' premiered in the 2009 [[Los Angeles Film Festival]]. Dole said they had serious concerns about the film's accuracy and they urged festival officials to \"immediately cease and desist\" their sponsorship of the film.<ref name=\"Edelman\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bananasthemovie.com/wp-content/uploads/resources/letter_from_dole_may8_09.pdf |title=Letter from Dole, May 8, 2009 |first=Scott A.|last=Edelman |work=bananasthemovie.com |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=October 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bananasthemovie.com/interview-with-director-fredrik-gertten/ |title=Interview with director Fredrik Gertten &#124; BANANAS!* |publisher=Bananasthemovie.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://svt.se/2.33782/1.1591791/bananas_far_inte_tavla_pa_festival |title=Bananas f\u00e5r inte t\u00e4vla p\u00e5 festival \u2013 Regionala nyheter |publisher=svt.se |accessdate=2012-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006015213/http://www.svt.se/2.33782/1.1591791/bananas_far_inte_tavla_pa_festival |archivedate=2012-10-06 }}</ref><ref name=\"bananasthemovie_com-_article\">{{cite web|title=About the film \u2013 BANANAS!*|url=http://www.bananasthemovie.com/about-the-film/#article}} 11 June 2009 \u2013 bananasthemovie.com</ref> The festival officials allowed the film to be screened, but it was not allowed to compete for placement in the competition. In addition, festival officials distributed information before the film's screening that indicated Dole believed the film to be factually inaccurate.\n\nAlthough the film was screened with a disclaimer from the festival, Gertten was subsequently sued for defamation by Dole.<ref name=\"Deutcsh\">{{cite news |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/businesstechnology/2009346592_apusdolebananaworkers.html |title=Dole sues 'Bananas!' filmmaker, alleges defamation |first=Linda |last=Deutcsh |agency=[[Associated Press]] |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=July 9, 2009 |publisher=[[The Seattle Times Company]] |location=Seattle, WA, USA |accessdate=October 4, 2012}}</ref> The lawsuit was dropped on October 15, 2009, and in November 2010 a court in Los Angeles found in favour of the movie crew making it possible to release the movie in the US, and ordering Dole to pay SEK 1.4 million (roughly US$200,000) to the filmmakers.<ref name=\"Mlik\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/film-tv/-filmen-bananas-vann-mot-dole |title=Filmen \"Bananas\" vann mot Dole |trans-title=The film \"Bananas\" won against Dole |language=Swedish |first=Nora |last=Mlik |publisher=Dn.se |location=Stockholm, Sweden |accessdate=October 6, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116171719/http://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/film-tv/-filmen-bananas-vann-mot-dole |archivedate=January 16, 2013 }} {{Google translation|en|sv|http://www.dn.se/kultur-noje/film-tv/-filmen-bananas-vann-mot-dole|Google  machine translation of this article}}</ref>\n\nGertten's sequel ''[[Big Boys Gone Bananas!*]]'' documents Dole's reactions to ''Bananas!*''.\n\nThe Nicaraguan DBCP awards against Dole were overturned in July 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title= Judge throws out verdict awarding millions to Dole workers |newspaper= [[Los Angeles Times]] |author= Victoria Kim |date= July 16, 2010 |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2010/jul/16/local/la-me-dole-20100716  |accessdate= September 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013 [[Oxfam]] demanded Dole remove its \"Ethical Choice\" labels from its bananas in New Zealand until it improved treatment of its workers in [[the Philippines]], but Dole said Oxfam was trying to \"destroy the Dole brand\" in favour of other suppliers.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://www.3news.co.nz/Dole-bananas-not-ethical---Oxfam/tabid/1160/articleID/299404/Default.aspx |work=3 News NZ |title= Dole bananas not ethical \u2013 Oxfam| date=May 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn Oct 2018 Myanmar Government blacklisted Thailand subsidiary of Dole after investigation found that one of its factory in Thailand exploited Myanmar migrant workers by demanding payments for visas, medical check-ups and work permit fees. Myanmar migrant workers are also prevented from taking paid annual leave. About 130 Myanmar migrants who took annual leaves were prevented from returning to work and got fired instead.<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.mmtimes.com/news/govt-blacklists-dole-thailand-over-labour-dispute.html |work=MyanmarTimes MM |title= Govt blacklists Dole-Thailand over labour dispute| date=Oct 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Labeling of genetically engineered foods in California===\nIn 2012, Dole Packaged Foods contributed $171,261 to a $46 million political campaign known as \"The Coalition Against The Costly Food Labeling Proposition, sponsored by Farmers and Food Producers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcet.org/news/ballotbrief/elections2012/propositions/prop-37-funding-genetically-engineered-food.html |title=Who's Funding Prop 37, Labeling for Genetically Engineered Foods? &#124; Propositions &#124; Elections 2012 |publisher=KCET.org |date= |accessdate=2015-06-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n; Media\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YkI3zkQ4WBo|title=Why The Banana Business Of Chiquita And Dole Is At Risk|publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=2019-04-21}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Portal|Hawaii|Los Angeles|Food|Companies}}\n* {{Official website|www.dole.com}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120214183130/http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/10/10303.html Yahoo! - Dole Food Company, Inc. Company Profile]\n\n{{Dole Food Company}}\n{{Pineapples}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Dole Food Company| ]]\n[[Category:Agriculture companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Food manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Multinational food companies]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the United States]]\n[[Category:Pineapple production]]\n[[Category:Business in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Westlake Village, California]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1851]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1851]]\n[[Category:1851 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Companies formerly listed on the New York Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Banana production]]\n[[Category:Fruit production]]\n[[Category:2013 mergers and acquisitions]]\n[[Category:Dole family]]\n", "name_user": "Alfredno1", "label": "safe", "comment": "2019 update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dole_Food_Company"}
{"title_page": "Lamborghini 350 GT", "text_new": "{{cleanup|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name          = Lamborghini 350 GT\n|image         = Lamborghini 350 GT 1964.jpg\n|manufacturer  = [[Carrozzeria Touring]] for<br>[[Lamborghini]]<ref name=Lambo_350GT/>\n|production    = May 1964\u20131966<ref name=CFI>{{cite web|title=Lamborghini 350, 400 & Islero|url=http://www.carsfromitaly.net/lambo/350_400_islero.html#350gt|work=CarsFromItaly.net|accessdate=9 January 2010}}</ref><br>120 built<ref name=Lambo_350GT/>\n|assembly      = Italy: [[Sant'Agata Bolognese|Sant'Agata]]<ref name=CFI/>\n|predecessor   = [[Lamborghini 350GTV]]\n|successor     = [[Lamborghini 400GT]]\n|class         = [[Grand tourer]] \n|body_style    = 2-[[vehicle door|door]] [[coup\u00e9]]\n|layout        = [[FR layout]]\n|engine        = {{convert|3464|cc|1|abbr=on}} 60\u00b0 aluminium [[Lamborghini V12|V12]] [[DOHC]]\n|powerout      = {{convert|280|bhp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|325|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of [[torque]]\n|transmission  = [[list of ZF transmissions#5-speed longitudinal|5-speed ZF]] [[manual transmission|manual]]<ref name=CFI/>\n|wheelbase     = {{convert|2550|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|width         = {{convert|1730|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|height        = {{convert|1220|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|weight        = {{convert|1450|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|related       = \n|designer      = [[Carrozzeria Touring]]\n|sp            = uk\n}}\n[[File:Lambo350GT 6815.jpg|right|thumb|250px|1965 Lamborghini 350GT]]\n[[File:Lambo350GT 6821.jpg|right|thumb|250px|1965 Lamborghini 350GT rear detail]]\n[[File:Lambo350GT 6820.jpg|right|thumb|250px|1965 Lamborghini 350GT engine]]\n[[File:Rear of Lamborghini 350GT 6826.jpg|right|thumb|250px|1965 Lamborghini 350GT rear]]\nThe '''Lamborghini 350 GT''' was a [[grand tourer]] manufactured by Lamborghini between 1964 and 1966. It was the first [[production vehicle]] produced by Lamborghini.<ref name=Lambo_350GT>{{cite web|title=Lamborghini \u2013 History \u2013 Masterpieces \u2013 350 GT |url=http://www.lamborghini.com/2006/lamboSitenormal.asp?lang=eng |work=Automobili Lamborghini Holding Spa |publisher=Lamborghini.com |accessdate=9 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107131615/http://www.lamborghini.com/2006/lamboSitenormal.asp?lang=eng |archivedate= 7 January 2010 }}</ref> The 350 GT was based on the earlier [[Lamborghini 350GTV|Lamborghini 350 GTV]] and was equipped with a 3.5 liter [[V12 engine]] and a 2-door [[coup\u00e9]] body by [[Carrozzeria Touring Superleggera|Carrozzeria Touring]]. The 350 GT debuted at the March [[Geneva Motor Show#1964|1964 Geneva Motor Show]] and production began the following May. The success of this model ensured the company's survival, establishing it as a viable competitor with rival manufacturer [[Ferrari]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Harvey|first=Chris|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/59246925|title=The Lamborghinis: A Collector's Guide|date=1982|publisher=Motor Racing|year=|isbn=0-900549-69-6|location=London|pages=|oclc=59246925}}</ref><ref name=Complete_Lambo>{{cite web |url=http://www.petelyons.com/Books.html |title=The Complete Book of Lamborghini |author=Pete Lyons |publisher=Publications International, 1988 |access-date=2010-05-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504060602/http://petelyons.com/books.html |archive-date=2015-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=CFI/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Initial design team===\nAfter the testing of his prototype Lamborghini engine in May 1963, then-lead engineer [[Giotto Bizzarrini]] left the company.<ref name=\":0\" /> The following month [[Ferruccio Lamborghini]] tasked engineer [[Gian Paolo Dallara]] with developing a production version of Bizzarrini's [[Lamborghini 350GTV|350GTV]] grand tourer.<ref name=\"Complete_Lambo\" /> Dallara was assisted in this project by engineer [[Paolo Stanzani]] and test driver [[Bob Wallace (test driver)|Bob Wallace]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDallara and Stanzani quickly realized that the 350 GTV was not properly designed for mass production. They began working in parallel on two projects that would result in the production 350 GT. First, they began de-tuning the original Bizzarrini engine and redesigning the original Bizzarrini chassis for street use.<ref name=\":0\" /> Second, they started readying the 350 GTV for its late-October 1963 [[Turin Auto Show]] debut, where Lamborghini hoped it would raise interest in the eventual production 350 GT.<ref name=\"Pasini_GTV\">Pasini, Stefano \"Lamborghini 350 GTV.\" Rivista Lamborghini Review, 1991</ref>\n===Redesigning the GTV Prototype===\nAs equipped to the 350 GTV, the Bizzarrini-designed 3.5 liter V12 was essentially a race motor, potentially developing {{Convert|400|hp|kW}} at 11,000rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.400gt.com/articles/EarlyLambo/Biz_Honda.htm|title=The Lamborghini V-12: A Japanese Connection?|last=Lyons|first=Pete|date=1988|website=excerpt from \"The Complete Book of Lamborghini|publisher=Beekman House|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925104412/http://www.400gt.com/articles/EarlyLambo/Biz_Honda.htm|archive-date=25 September 2018|access-date=}}</ref>  In order to fit his grand touring car with a smoother, more pleasant, longer-lasting engine that would be \"good for 40,000 hard miles between services,\" Ferruccio had Dallara and Wallace de-tune a version of this prototype GTV motor for street use.<ref name=Complete_Lambo/><ref name=\":0\" /> This included:<ref name=Complete_Lambo/>\n*Replacing the elaborate and costly racing-style [[Dry sump|dry sump oiling system]] with a conventional [[Wet sump|wet sump system]]\n*Reducing the [[compression ratio]] from 11.0:1 or above to 9.4:1\n*Cutting back on the exotic materials specified for the [[crankshaft]] and other components to reduce cost\n*Relocating the [[Distributor|distributors]] to more accessible positions on the fronts of the exhaust [[Camshaft|camshafts]]\n*Adoption of a single, very tall Lamborghini-made [[oil filter]]\n*Replacing the expensive 36&nbsp;mm down-draft racing [[Weber carburetor|Weber carburetors]] with conventional side-draft 40 DCOE Webers\n*Softening the [[Camshaft#Duration|cam profiles]] for smoother running during street driving\n\nThis first \"detuned\" L350 engine was tested on October 3, 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.400gt.com/articles/first_test/first_test.htm |title=The First Lamborghini L350 Engine Test}}</ref> The result{{mdash}}later fit in the 350&nbsp;GT{{mdash}}was a very capable 270&nbsp;bhp power plant that could reach {{convert|254|km/h|0}} in top form.<ref name=Complete_Lambo/><ref name=Riding_The_Bull>{{cite web|url=http://www.hemmings.com/hsx/stories/2008/09/01/hmn_feature13.html |title=Riding The Bull |publisher=Hemmings, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWhile this 350&nbsp;GT design work continued, the 350 GTV prototype was rushed to completion for the upcoming October 26 press meeting and the subsequent inauguration of the Turin Auto Show on the 30th.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=Pasini_GTV/>  The 350GTV was shown at the Turin Auto Show with the original Bizzarrini \"racing\" V-12 engine{{mdash}}with its downdraft webers, rear distributors, etc.{{mdash}}displayed alongside as it was not \"adapted to the chassis.\"<ref name=Pasini_GTV/> The car was a static display with the suspension arms simply tack-welded in place and the engine not installed.<ref name=Complete_Lambo/><ref name=\"Pasini_GTV\" /> Lukewarm reaction to the car caused Ferruccio Lamborghini to postpone plans for immediate production and move on to introducing Dallara's new 350&nbsp;GT design.<ref name=Complete_Lambo/>\n\nIn March 1964, only 5 months after the debut of the GTV in Turin, the \"redesigned GTV\"{{mdash}}now called the 350&nbsp;GT{{mdash}}was debuted at the Geneva Auto Show.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was greeted with sufficient enthusiasm that Ferruccio decided to proceed with production in May 1964.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=Complete_Lambo/>\n\n===Manufacturing and assembly===\nThe manufacture of the bodies was entrusted to [[Carrozzeria Touring|Touring]] of Milan, who used their patented [[Superleggera]] method of construction to fix [[aluminium alloy]] panels directly to a tubular structure. The first 350&nbsp;GT frame was fabricated by [[Neri and Bonacini]], who continued to act as Lamborghini's chassis supplier until production of the 350&nbsp;GT was underway, when the job was turned over to Marchesi.<ref>[[Lamborghini 400GT Monza]]</ref>  Chassis and bodies were mated at Touring, which then delivered the complete assemblies{{mdash}}with even the bumpers in place{{mdash}}to the Lamborghini factory.  The cars could be ordered in these [http://www.400gt.com/misc/350colors.jpg colors]. \n\nThe first 350&nbsp;GT chassis and body, delivered to the Lamborghini factory on March 9, 1964, was named No. 101 (Touring No. 17001).  That same month No. 101 debuted at the Geneva show.  The first customer delivery of a 350&nbsp;GT was No. 104 (Touring No. 17004), delivered on July 31, 1964.\n\nLamborghini produced one hundred-twenty 350&nbsp;GTs before replacing it with the [[Lamborghini 400 GT]] in 1966.<ref name=Lambo_350GT/>  Many 350&nbsp;GTs were subsequently fit with the larger 4.0 litre engine used in the 400 GT.\n\n==Specifications==\nThe 350&nbsp;GT had an all-[[aluminium alloy]] V12 engine mated to a [[list of ZF transmissions#5-speed longitudinal|five-speed ZF]] [[manual transmission]]. It had an aluminium body (some had steel bodies), a Salisbury differential, four-wheel independent suspension, and [[vacuum servo]]-assisted [[Girling brakes|Girling]] [[disc brake]]s all round. The 350 GT was originally fitted with [[Pirelli Cinturato]] 205VR15 tyres (CN72).<ref name=CFI/>\n\nIt had a wheelbase of {{convert|2550|mm|1}}, with a front and rear [[axle track]] of {{convert|1380|mm|1}}.  It measured {{convert|4640|mm|1}} long by {{convert|1730|mm|1}} wide and was by {{convert|1220|mm|1}} high.  With its [[curb weight|kerb weight]] of {{convert|1450|kg|0}}, the 350&nbsp;GT could accelerate from {{convert|0|to|100|km/h|1}} in 6.8&nbsp;seconds, and from {{convert|0|to|100|mph|0}} in 16.3&nbsp;seconds, and go on to reach a top speed of {{convert|254|km/h|0}}.<ref name=Lambo_350GT/><ref name=CFI/><ref name=Riding_The_Bull/>\n\n===Redesign features===\n\nThe 350&nbsp;GT shared a number of features with the 350&nbsp;GTV prototype, including a four-wheel [[independent suspension]], [[Lamborghini V12|quad-cam V12]], and an aluminium body. A number of revisions and refinements were made due to the suggestions of the Neri and Bonacini racing development shop and test driver Bob Wallace.  Fixed headlights replaced the prototype's rotationally hidden variety, and twin-barrel side-draught [[Weber carburetor|Weber]] 40 DCOE 2 [[carburetor|carburettors]] reduced the height of the engine, thereby negating the clearance problems of the GTV prototype, and giving the car the exceptionally low hood line Ferruccio desired.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Chassis===\n\nAs was the case with the motor, Bizzarrini's GTV \"racing\" chassis design was the basis of Dallara's 350&nbsp;GT \"street\" chassis. Using far heavier materials, Dallara created an extremely strong chassis from square-section tubing which provided easy entry and exit through the doors, aided in the quietness of the car, and provided a solid platform on which to mount the body, much like the Aston Martin DB4.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Suspension===\n\nThe suspension was fully independent, with unequal-length wishbones and concentric coil-spring-damper units. The rear suspension wishbones were offset towards the spring mountings to resist driving and braking torque, which provided superior handling.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Engine===\n\nQuality control of the early {{convert|3464|cc|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} engines was very high. Each one underwent tests for 24 hours on a Schenk Walge dynamometer, being run for the first 12 hours under electric power, and then with gasoline at increasing speeds, producing {{convert|280|bhp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 6500 rpm and {{convert|325|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of [[torque]] at 4500 rpm.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.lambocars.com/classic_gt/350_gt_specifications.html\n|website=Lambocars.com\n|title=350 GT specifications\n|accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> A detailed analysis was made of its behavior before installation in the car for at least 500 kilometres of mixed-test running by Wallace.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Lamborghini 350 GT}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lamborghini road car timeline 1963-1989}}\n{{Lamborghini}}\n\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Lamborghini vehicles|350GT]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Group 4 cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1963]]\n", "text_old": "{{cleanup|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n|name          = Lamborghini 350 GT\n|image         = Lamborghini 350 GT 1964.jpg\n|manufacturer  = [[Carrozzeria Touring]] for<br>[[Lamborghini]]<ref name=Lambo_350GT/>\n|production    = May 1964\u20131966<ref name=CFI>{{cite web|title=Lamborghini 350, 400 & Islero|url=http://www.carsfromitaly.net/lambo/350_400_islero.html#350gt|work=CarsFromItaly.net|accessdate=9 January 2010}}</ref><br>120 built<ref name=Lambo_350GT/>\n|assembly      = Italy: [[Sant'Agata Bolognese|Sant'Agata]]<ref name=CFI/>\n|predecessor   = [[Lamborghini 350GTV]]\n|successor     = [[Lamborghini 400GT]]\n|class         = [[Grand tourer]] \n|body_style    = 2-[[vehicle door|door]] [[coup\u00e9]]\n|layout        = [[FR layout]]\n|engine        = {{convert|3464|cc|1|abbr=on}} 60\u00b0 aluminium [[Lamborghini V12|V12]] [[DOHC]]\n|powerout      = {{convert|280|bhp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} and {{convert|325|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of [[torque]]\n|transmission  = [[list of ZF transmissions#5-speed longitudinal|5-speed ZF]] [[manual transmission|manual]]<ref name=CFI/>\n|wheelbase     = {{convert|2550|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|width         = {{convert|1730|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|height        = {{convert|1220|mm|1|abbr=on}}\n|weight        = {{convert|1450|kg|0|abbr=on}}\n|related       = \n|designer      = [[Carrozzeria Touring]]\n|sp            = uk\n}}\n[[File:Lambo350GT 6815.jpg|right|thumb|250px|1965 Lamborghini 350GT]]\n[[File:Lambo350GT 6821.jpg|right|thumb|250px|1965 Lamborghini 350GT rear detail]]\n[[File:Lambo350GT 6820.jpg|right|thumb|250px|1965 Lamborghini 350GT engine]]\n[[File:Rear of Lamborghini 350GT 6826.jpg|right|thumb|250px|1965 Lamborghini 350GT rear]]\nThe '''Lamborghini 350 GT''' was a [[grand tourer]] manufactured by Lamborghini between 1964 and 1966. It was the first [[production vehicle]] produced by Lamborghini.<ref name=Lambo_350GT>{{cite web|title=Lamborghini \u2013 History \u2013 Masterpieces \u2013 350 GT |url=http://www.lamborghini.com/2006/lamboSitenormal.asp?lang=eng |work=Automobili Lamborghini Holding Spa |publisher=Lamborghini.com |accessdate=9 January 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107131615/http://www.lamborghini.com/2006/lamboSitenormal.asp?lang=eng |archivedate= 7 January 2010 }}</ref> The 350 GT was based on the earlier [[Lamborghini 350GTV|Lamborghini 350 GTV]] and was equipped with a 3.5 liter [[V12 engine]] and a 2-door [[coup\u00e9]] body by [[Carrozzeria Touring Superleggera|Carrozzeria Touring]]. The 350 GT debuted at the March [[Geneva Motor Show#1964|1964 Geneva Motor Show]] and production began the following May. The success of this model ensured the company's survival, establishing it as a viable competitor with rival manufacturer [[Ferrari]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Harvey|first=Chris|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/59246925|title=The Lamborghinis: A Collector's Guide|date=1982|publisher=Motor Racing|year=|isbn=0-900549-69-6|location=London|pages=|oclc=59246925}}</ref><ref name=Complete_Lambo>{{cite web |url=http://www.petelyons.com/Books.html |title=The Complete Book of Lamborghini |author=Pete Lyons |publisher=Publications International, 1988 |access-date=2010-05-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504060602/http://petelyons.com/books.html |archive-date=2015-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=CFI/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Initial design team===\nAfter the testing of his prototype Lamborghini engine in May 1963, then-lead engineer [[Giotto Bizzarrini]] left the company.<ref name=\":0\" /> The following month [[Ferruccio Lamborghini]] tasked engineer [[Gian Paolo Dallara]] with developing a production version of Bizzarrini's [[Lamborghini 350GTV|350GTV]] grand tourer.<ref name=\"Complete_Lambo\" /> Dallara was assisted in this project by engineer [[Paolo Stanzani]] and test driver [[Bob Wallace (test driver)|Bob Wallace]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nDallara and Stanzani quickly realized that the 350 GTV was not properly designed for mass production. They began working in parallel on two projects that would result in the production 350 GT. First, they began de-tuning the original Bizzarrini engine and redesigning the original Bizzarrini chassis for street use.<ref name=\":0\" /> Second, they started readying the 350 GTV for its late-October 1963 [[Turin Auto Show]] debut, where Lamborghini hoped it would raise interest in the eventual production 350 GT.<ref name=\"Pasini_GTV\">Pasini, Stefano \"Lamborghini 350 GTV.\" Rivista Lamborghini Review, 1991</ref>\n===Redesigning the GTV Prototype===\nAs equipped to the 350 GTV, the Bizzarrini-designed 3.5 liter V12 was essentially a race motor, potentially developing {{Convert|400|hp|kW}} at 11,000rpm.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.400gt.com/articles/EarlyLambo/Biz_Honda.htm|title=The Lamborghini V-12: A Japanese Connection?|last=Lyons|first=Pete|date=1988|website=excerpt from \"The Complete Book of Lamborghini|publisher=Beekman House|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925104412/http://www.400gt.com/articles/EarlyLambo/Biz_Honda.htm|archive-date=25 September 2018|access-date=}}</ref>  In order to fit his grand touring car with a smoother, more pleasant, longer-lasting engine that would be \"good for 40,000 hard miles between services,\" Ferruccio had Dallara and Wallace de-tune a version of this prototype GTV motor for street use.<ref name=Complete_Lambo/><ref name=\":0\" /> This included:<ref name=Complete_Lambo/>\n*Replacing the elaborate and costly racing-style [[Dry sump|dry sump oiling system]] with a conventional [[Wet sump|wet sump system]]\n*Reducing the [[compression ratio]] from 11.0:1 or above to 9.4:1\n*Cutting back on the exotic materials specified for the [[crankshaft]] and other components to reduce cost\n*Relocating the [[Distributor|distributors]] to more accessible positions on the fronts of the exhaust [[Camshaft|camshafts]]\n*Adoption of a single, very tall Lamborghini-made [[oil filter]]\n*Replacing the expensive 36&nbsp;mm vertical racing [[Weber carburetor|Weber carburetors]] with conventional side-draft 40 DCOE Webers\n*Softening the [[Camshaft#Duration|cam profiles]] for smoother running during street driving\n\nThis first \"detuned\" L350 engine was tested on October 3, 1963.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.400gt.com/articles/first_test/first_test.htm |title=The First Lamborghini L350 Engine Test}}</ref> The result{{mdash}}later fit in the 350&nbsp;GT{{mdash}}was a very capable 270&nbsp;bhp power plant that could reach {{convert|254|km/h|0}} in top form.<ref name=Complete_Lambo/><ref name=Riding_The_Bull>{{cite web|url=http://www.hemmings.com/hsx/stories/2008/09/01/hmn_feature13.html |title=Riding The Bull |publisher=Hemmings, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWhile this 350&nbsp;GT design work continued, the 350 GTV prototype was rushed to completion for the upcoming October 26 press meeting and the subsequent inauguration of the Turin Auto Show on the 30th.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=Pasini_GTV/>  The 350GTV was shown at the Turin Auto Show with the original Bizzarrini \"racing\" V-12 engine{{mdash}}with its downdraft webers, rear distributors, etc.{{mdash}}displayed alongside as it was not \"adapted to the chassis.\"<ref name=Pasini_GTV/> The car was a static display with the suspension arms simply tack-welded in place and the engine not installed.<ref name=Complete_Lambo/><ref name=\"Pasini_GTV\" /> Lukewarm reaction to the car caused Ferruccio Lamborghini to postpone plans for immediate production and move on to introducing Dallara's new 350&nbsp;GT design.<ref name=Complete_Lambo/>\n\nIn March 1964, only 5 months after the debut of the GTV in Turin, the \"redesigned GTV\"{{mdash}}now called the 350&nbsp;GT{{mdash}}was debuted at the Geneva Auto Show.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was greeted with sufficient enthusiasm that Ferruccio decided to proceed with production in May 1964.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=Complete_Lambo/>\n\n===Manufacturing and assembly===\nThe manufacture of the bodies was entrusted to [[Carrozzeria Touring|Touring]] of Milan, who used their patented [[Superleggera]] method of construction to fix [[aluminium alloy]] panels directly to a tubular structure. The first 350&nbsp;GT frame was fabricated by [[Neri and Bonacini]], who continued to act as Lamborghini's chassis supplier until production of the 350&nbsp;GT was underway, when the job was turned over to Marchesi.<ref>[[Lamborghini 400GT Monza]]</ref>  Chassis and bodies were mated at Touring, which then delivered the complete assemblies{{mdash}}with even the bumpers in place{{mdash}}to the Lamborghini factory.  The cars could be ordered in these [http://www.400gt.com/misc/350colors.jpg colors]. \n\nThe first 350&nbsp;GT chassis and body, delivered to the Lamborghini factory on March 9, 1964, was named No. 101 (Touring No. 17001).  That same month No. 101 debuted at the Geneva show.  The first customer delivery of a 350&nbsp;GT was No. 104 (Touring No. 17004), delivered on July 31, 1964.\n\nLamborghini produced one hundred-twenty 350&nbsp;GTs before replacing it with the [[Lamborghini 400 GT]] in 1966.<ref name=Lambo_350GT/>  Many 350&nbsp;GTs were subsequently fit with the larger 4.0 litre engine used in the 400 GT.\n\n==Specifications==\nThe 350&nbsp;GT had an all-[[aluminium alloy]] V12 engine mated to a [[list of ZF transmissions#5-speed longitudinal|five-speed ZF]] [[manual transmission]]. It had an aluminium body (some had steel bodies), a Salisbury differential, four-wheel independent suspension, and [[vacuum servo]]-assisted [[Girling brakes|Girling]] [[disc brake]]s all round. The 350 GT was originally fitted with [[Pirelli Cinturato]] 205VR15 tyres (CN72).<ref name=CFI/>\n\nIt had a wheelbase of {{convert|2550|mm|1}}, with a front and rear [[axle track]] of {{convert|1380|mm|1}}.  It measured {{convert|4640|mm|1}} long by {{convert|1730|mm|1}} wide and was by {{convert|1220|mm|1}} high.  With its [[curb weight|kerb weight]] of {{convert|1450|kg|0}}, the 350&nbsp;GT could accelerate from {{convert|0|to|100|km/h|1}} in 6.8&nbsp;seconds, and from {{convert|0|to|100|mph|0}} in 16.3&nbsp;seconds, and go on to reach a top speed of {{convert|254|km/h|0}}.<ref name=Lambo_350GT/><ref name=CFI/><ref name=Riding_The_Bull/>\n\n===Redesign features===\n\nThe 350&nbsp;GT shared a number of features with the 350&nbsp;GTV prototype, including a four-wheel [[independent suspension]], [[Lamborghini V12|quad-cam V12]], and an aluminium body. A number of revisions and refinements were made due to the suggestions of the Neri and Bonacini racing development shop and test driver Bob Wallace.  Fixed headlights replaced the prototype's rotationally hidden variety, and twin-barrel side-draught [[Weber carburetor|Weber]] 40 DCOE 2 [[carburetor|carburettors]] reduced the height of the engine, thereby negating the clearance problems of the GTV prototype, and giving the car the exceptionally low hood line Ferruccio desired.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Chassis===\n\nAs was the case with the motor, Bizzarrini's GTV \"racing\" chassis design was the basis of Dallara's 350&nbsp;GT \"street\" chassis. Using far heavier materials, Dallara created an extremely strong chassis from square-section tubing which provided easy entry and exit through the doors, aided in the quietness of the car, and provided a solid platform on which to mount the body, much like the Aston Martin DB4.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Suspension===\n\nThe suspension was fully independent, with unequal-length wishbones and concentric coil-spring-damper units. The rear suspension wishbones were offset towards the spring mountings to resist driving and braking torque, which provided superior handling.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Engine===\n\nQuality control of the early {{convert|3464|cc|L|1|abbr=on|order=flip}} engines was very high. Each one underwent tests for 24 hours on a Schenk Walge dynamometer, being run for the first 12 hours under electric power, and then with gasoline at increasing speeds, producing {{convert|280|bhp|PS kW|0|abbr=on}} at 6500 rpm and {{convert|325|Nm|0|abbr=on}} of [[torque]] at 4500 rpm.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.lambocars.com/classic_gt/350_gt_specifications.html\n|website=Lambocars.com\n|title=350 GT specifications\n|accessdate=2018-09-17}}</ref> A detailed analysis was made of its behavior before installation in the car for at least 500 kilometres of mixed-test running by Wallace.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Lamborghini 350 GT}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lamborghini road car timeline 1963-1989}}\n{{Lamborghini}}\n\n[[Category:Coup\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:First car made by manufacturer]]\n[[Category:Lamborghini vehicles|350GT]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Group 4 cars]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 1963]]\n", "name_user": "Prova MO", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRedesigning the GTV Prototype:vertical -> down-draft. this is more common nomenclature", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lamborghini_350_GT"}
{"title_page": "Nigger in the woodpile", "text_new": "{{short description|Expression indicating something suspicious or wrong}}\n{{For|the film|A Nigger in the Woodpile}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n[[File:The Nigger in the Woodpile.jpg|thumb|A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] parody, titled \"\"The Nigger\" in the Woodpile\", lampooned what they claimed were Republican efforts to play down the antislavery plank in their 1860 platform. Republican candidate [[Abraham Lincoln]], who had worked as a laborer splitting wooden rails as a young man, is sitting on top of the pile (believed to have been drawn by [[Louis Maurer]])]]\n'''''Nigger in the woodpile''''' or '''''nigger in the fence''''' is a [[figure of speech]] originating in the [[United States]] meaning \"some fact of considerable importance that is not disclosed\u2014something suspicious or wrong\".<ref name=\"Conforth2013\">{{cite book|author=Bruce M. Conforth|title=African American Folksong and American Cultural Politics: The Lawrence Gellert Story|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B2mqs_FvabIC&pg=PA145|date=16 May 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8489-2|page=145}}</ref>\n\nCommonly used in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, usage has declined since then, and use of the phrase by public figures has often been followed by criticism over the racism of the term \"[[nigger]]\". Thus, the phrase has been supplanted by \"''a tiger in the woodpile''\",  and also by the similar (though not entirely synonymous) phrases \"[[Skeleton in the closet (idiom)|skeleton in the closet]]\", \"[[fly in the ointment]]\", and \"[[elephant in the room]]\" which avoid the connotation.\n\n== Origin ==\nBoth the \"fence\" and \"woodpile\" variants developed about the same time in the period of 1840\u201350,<ref>\"nigger, n. and adj., \u00a7P2\" OED Online. Oxford University Press, June 2017. Web. 11 July 2017.</ref> when the [[Underground Railroad]] was flourishing. The evidence is slight, but it is presumed that they were derived from actual instances of the concealment of [[fugitive slaves]] in their flight north under piles of firewood or within hiding places in stone walls.<ref>\"nigger, n. and adj., etymology\" OED Online. Oxford University Press, June 2017. Web. 11 July 2017.</ref><ref>\"Heavens to Betsy\" (1955, Harper & Row) by [[Charles Earle Funk]]</ref> Another possible origin comes from the practice of transporting [[pulpwood]] on special railroad cars. In the era of slavery, the pulpwood cars were built with an outer frame with the wood being stacked inside in moderately neat rows and stacks. However, given the nature of the cars, it was possible to smuggle persons in the pile itself, possibly giving rise to the term.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n== Usage ==\nAn American film comedy titled ''[[A Nigger in the Woodpile]]'' was released in 1904,<ref name=Stewart>{{cite book|last=Stewart|first=Jacqueline Najuma|title=Migrating to the Movies: Cinema and Black Urban Modernity|year=2005|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=0-520-23350-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/migratingtomovie0000stew/page/1 1]|url=https://archive.org/details/migratingtomovie0000stew/page/1}}</ref> and the idiom was common in literature and film during the 1920s and 1930s. Examples include the original 1927 version of the [[Hardy Boys]] book ''[[The House on the Cliff]]'' (pg. 77), where Frank Hardy uses the expression (removed when the story was revised in 1959), and the old-time band [[Skillet Lickers]] recording a song called \"Nigger in the Woodpile\" in 1930.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/skillet-lickers-vol-4-1929-1930-mw0000007207|title=Skillet Lickers, Vol. 4: 1929\u20131930 \u2013 The Skillet Lickers \u2013 Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards \u2013 AllMusic|author=Steve Leggett|publisher=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\n[[Dr. Seuss]] used the term in a 1929 cartoon \"Cross-Section of The World's Most Prosperous Department Store\", wherein customers browse through a department store looking for items to make their lives more difficult. The panels show a series of scenarios based on popular figures of speech: a man with a net trying to catch a [[fly in the ointment|fly for his ointment]], another looking at [[monkeywrenching|monkey wrenches to throw into his machinery]], one examining [[needle in a haystack (disambiguation)|haystacks with matching needles]], and finally a man looking at a selection of niggers for his woodpile.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/05/27/racist-dr-seuss_n_7446806.html|title=One Particularly Upsetting And Racist Dr. Seuss Cartoon Is Heading To Auction|first=Priscilla|last=Frank|date=27 May 2015|work=Huff Post}}</ref>\n\nThe author Zane Grey's 1921 novel ''The Mysterious Rider'' uses the expression at least twice throughout the story to explain a situation in which facts were purposefully omitted.\nIn the 1929 RKO film \"Street Girl,\" the phrase is spoken by [[Joseph Cawthorn]], but it has been erased from the print that Turner Classic Movies shows.\n\nIn the 1930 [[pre-Code]] comedy ''[[Not So Dumb]]'', Marion Davies consistently and constantly convolutes common idioms and expressions. After finally finding misplaced billiard balls that she had used as darning eggs, she proudly exclaims, \"I just knew there was a woodpile in the nigger when I couldn't find 'em.\"{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n\nA visual gag in the [[Looney Tunes]] cartoon ''[[Porky's Railroad]]'' from 1937 refers to the phrase.\n\nThe phrase is also used in ''[[The Razor's Edge]]'' by [[Somerset Maugham]]. One of the American characters, on the brink of closing a business deal, says to the narrator, \"I'll fly down to Texas to give the outfit the once-over, and you bet I'll keep my eyes peeled for a nigger in the woodpile before I cough up any ... dough.\"<ref>The Razor's Edge (Vintage International) (Part Seven, Chapter 3, p. 244).</ref>\n\n\nIn Chapter 3 of ''[[Absalom, Absalom]]'' William Faulkner uses the phrase when referring to the success of a cotton plantation: \"...some among his fellow citizens who believed even yet that there was a nigger in the woodpile somewhere.\" <ref>{{Cite book|title=Absalom, Absalom! : the corrected text|last=1897-1962.|first=Faulkner, William|date=1993|publisher=Modern Library|isbn=0679600728|edition= 1993 Modern Library |location=New York|pages=72|oclc=28378575}}</ref>\n\nComputer scientist [[Edsger W. Dijkstra]] uses the phrase in a published reply to referees ca 1975.\n<ref> https://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/EWD/transcriptions/EWD04xx/EWD470.html\n</ref>\n\nIn the book ''Your Health: A Corrective System of Exercising that Revolutionizes the Entire Field of Physical Education'', by Joseph H. Pilates in 1934, page 18 writes, \"This is the 'Nigger in the wood pile'.\"<ref>Pilates, Joseph H., (1934) Your Health: A Corrective System of Exercising that Revolutionizes the Entire Field of Physical Education. Published by Joseph H. Pilates.</ref>\n\nAgatha Christie used the phrase as the title of chapter 18 of the 1937 [[Hercule Poirot]] novel ''[[Dumb Witness]]'', which was later published in the U.S. as ''Poirot Loses a Client''. The chapter was later retitled \"A Cuckoo in the Nest\". A character also uses the phrase in Chapter 22 of her 1953 book \"After the Funeral\". The phrase was also used by a character in early editions of Christie's novel ''[[And Then There Were None]]'' (originally released under the title ''Ten Little Niggers''), but was changed in later editions to ''There's a [[fly in the ointment]]''. As late as 1952, in the novel ''[[They Do It with Mirrors]]'', published in the U.S. as ''Murder with Mirrors,'' she has a character use the phrase. It appears in editions published as late as 1985.  In her 1970 novel ''[[Passenger to Frankfurt]]'', she has a character use the phrase in chapter 23.\n\n[[W. C. Fields]] used variations of this phrase in two of his films: In ''[[You Can't Cheat an Honest Man]]'' (1939) he said there was \"an Ubangi in the fuel supply\", and in ''[[My Little Chickadee]]'' (1940) he said there was \"an Ethiopian in the fuel supply\".\n\nIn the song, \"This Could Be True\", [[Pat Kirkwood (actress)|Pat Kirkwood]] and [[Graham Payn]] sing the phrase in [[No\u00ebl Coward]]'s 1950 musical ''[[Ace of Clubs (musical)|Ace of Clubs]]''.\n\nPopular western author [[Louis L'Amour]] used a variant in ''Crossfire Trail'' (1954): \"Now there seemed to be a larger African in the woodpile, or several of them.\"\n\nPopular music group [[Supertramp]] used the phrase in the lyrics of their 1971 song 'Potter'. English band [[10cc]] also used the phrase in their song 'The Second Sitting for the Last Supper' from their album [[The Original Soundtrack]] from 1975.\n\nThe phrase declined in use during the 20th century, and now the occasional use of this phrase by public figures has often been followed by controversy and apology.\n\nIn July 2008, the leader of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|British Conservative Party]], [[David Cameron]], was urged to sack Conservative peer [[Lord Dixon-Smith]], who said in the [[House of Lords]] that concerns about government housing legislation were \"the nigger in the woodpile\".  Dixon-Smith said the phrase had \"slipped out without my thinking\", and that \"It was common parlance when I was younger\".<ref name=\"cameron\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/2273176/David-Cameron-urged-to-sack-Tory-peer-after-nigger-in-the-woodpile-remark.html|title=David Cameron urged to sack Tory peer after 'nigger in the woodpile' remark \u2013 David Cameron is facing calls to sack a Conservative peer who described concerns over government housing legislation as \"the nigger in the woodpile\" during a House of Lords debate.|author=Lucy Cockcroft|website=The Daily Telegraph|date=9 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, the phrase was again used by British Conservative Party politician [[Anne Marie Morris]] who said that [[Brexit]] without a deal with the European Union was the \"real nigger in the woodpile\". She later said \"The comment was totally unintentional. I apologise unreservedly for any offence caused.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40555639|title=MP Anne Marie Morris apologises for racist remark|date=10 July 2017|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-brexiteer-uk-leaving-eu-without-deal-n-word-in-the-woodpile-anne-marie-morris-newton-abbott-a7833786.html|title=Tory Brexiteer describes UK leaving EU without deal as 'real n***** in the woodpile'|date=10 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/tory-mp-racist-brexit-recording_uk_59638608e4b02e9bdb0e2c77?|title=Listen As Tory MP Recorded Saying Brexit No Deal Is A 'N***** In A Woodpile'|date=10 July 2017}}</ref> However, she was suspended the same day by the party's [[chief whip]], on the orders of party leader, the prime minister, [[Theresa May]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jul/10/tories-urgently-investigating-after-mp-uses-n-word-at-public-event|title=Theresa May orders Tory MP to be suspended after using N-word |date=10 July 2017|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The Conservative Party whip was restored to Morris on 12 December 2017, one day before a crucial vote on the Brexit process. Although Morris voted with the Conservative Government, the Government was defeated by four votes.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Anne Marie Morris: Tory MP has whip restored after racist remark | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42322022 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 12 December 2017 | access-date = 12 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2018 it was revealed that Irish race car driver and commentator [[Derek Daly]] had used the phrase in a radio interview in 1980.  He did so while describing how he was the only non-American on his new race team. Once it was revealed, Derek lost his commentator job. His son also lost his sponsor for the weekend.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jalopnik.com/conor-daly-loses-weekend-nascar-sponsorship-after-dads-1828590727|title=Conor Daly Loses Weekend NASCAR Sponsorship After Dad's Reported Use of the N-Word|last=King|first=Alanis|work=Jalopnik|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[Australian Communications and Media Authority]] (ACMA) ruled that radio station [[2GB]] breached the Commercial Radio Code of Practice when the broadcaster [[Alan Jones (radio broadcaster)|Alan Jones]] used a \"racially charged phrase\" during a segment in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-29/sydney-news-morning-briefing-friday-march-29/10950098|title=Jones used 'racially charged phrase'|date=29 March 2019|publisher=ABC News Australia}}</ref> ACMA received numerous complaints after Jones used the controversial phrase in August 2018, while discussing the looming second [[Liberal Party of Australia]] leadership spill. \"The nigger in the woodpile here, if one can use that expression \u2013 and I'm not going to yield to people who tell us that certain words in the language are forbidden \u2013 the person who's playing hard to get is [[Mathias Cormann]],\" Jones told listeners. ACMA found that, while the phrase was widely considered racist, its use in the broadcast didn't likely incite \"hatred\", \"serious contempt\" or \"severe ridicule\". 2GB's management agreed the term will not be used on-air again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acma.gov.au/articles/2019-03/2gb-breaches-decency-requirements|title=2GB breaches decency requirements|date=28 March 2019|publisher=Australian Communications and Media Authority}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, a Downing Street aide alleged that [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]] had used the phrase during a trade meeting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/nov/18/prince-andrew-used-n-word-former-no-10-aide-claims|title=Prince Andrew used the N-word, former No 10 aide claims|first=Jim Waterson Media|last=editor|date=18 November 2019|via=www.theguardian.com|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[The Dog in the Manger|Dog in the manger]]\n* [[Elephant in the room]]\n* [[Wolf in sheep's clothing]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wiktionary}}\n*[http://loc.harpweek.com/LCPoliticalCartoons/DisplayCartoonMedium.asp?MaxID=&UniqueID=4&Year=1860&YearMark= Racist parody of Republican platform] from 1860 Presidential campaign, in ''[[Harper's Weekly]]''\n*[http://www.utpjournals.com/product/utq/714/714_cariou.htm Epistemology of the Woodpile], ''[[University of Toronto]] Quarterly''\n*[http://hnn.us/articles/1828.html#11130301 History News Network blog post] about origins of term\n*[http://hnn.us/articles/1368.html#11180302 History News Network blog post] about a recent controversy\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=nlgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA72&#v=onepage&q&f=false Phrase used in 1918 advertisement for Patterson Publishing Company] The Rotarian magazine\n\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1840s]]\n[[Category:English phrases]]\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for people]]\n[[Category:Metaphors referring to people]]\n[[Category:Negro]]\n[[Category:American English idioms]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Expression indicating something suspicious or wrong}}\n{{For|the film|A Nigger in the Woodpile}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n[[File:The Nigger in the Woodpile.jpg|thumb|A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] parody, titled \"\"The Nigger\" in the Woodpile\", lampooned what they claimed were Republican efforts to play down the antislavery plank in their 1860 platform. Republican candidate [[Abraham Lincoln]], who had worked as a laborer splitting wooden rails as a young man, is sitting on top of the pile (believed to have been drawn by [[Louis Maurer]])]]\n'''''Nigger in the woodpile''''' or '''''nigger in the fence''''' is a [[figure of speech]] originating in the [[United States]] meaning \"some fact of considerable importance that is not disclosed\u2014something suspicious or wrong\".<ref name=\"Conforth2013\">{{cite book|author=Bruce M. Conforth|title=African American Folksong and American Cultural Politics: The Lawrence Gellert Story|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B2mqs_FvabIC&pg=PA145|date=16 May 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8489-2|page=145}}</ref>\n\nCommonly used in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, usage has declined since then, and use of the phrase by public figures has often been followed by criticism over the racism of the term \"[[nigger]]\". Thus, the phrase has been supplanted by \"''a tiger in the woodpile''\",  and also by the similar (though not entirely synonymous) phrases \"[[Skeleton in the closet (idiom)|skeleton in the closet]]\", \"[[fly in the ointment]]\", and \"[[elephant in the room]]\" which avoid the connotation.\n\n== Origin ==\nBoth the \"fence\" and \"woodpile\" variants developed about the same time in the period of 1840\u201350,<ref>\"nigger, n. and adj., \u00a7P2\" OED Online. Oxford University Press, June 2017. Web. 11 July 2017.</ref> when the [[Underground Railroad]] was flourishing. The evidence is slight, but it is presumed that they were derived from actual instances of the concealment of [[fugitive slaves]] in their flight north under piles of firewood or within hiding places in stone walls.<ref>\"nigger, n. and adj., etymology\" OED Online. Oxford University Press, June 2017. Web. 11 July 2017.</ref><ref>\"Heavens to Betsy\" (1955, Harper & Row) by [[Charles Earle Funk]]</ref> Another possible origin comes from the practice of transporting [[pulpwood]] on special railroad cars. In the era of slavery, the pulpwood cars were built with an outer frame with the wood being stacked inside in moderately neat rows and stacks. However, given the nature of the cars, it was possible to smuggle persons in the pile itself, possibly giving rise to the term.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n== Usage ==\nAn American film comedy titled ''[[A Nigger in the Woodpile]]'' was released in 1904,<ref name=Stewart>{{cite book|last=Stewart|first=Jacqueline Najuma|title=Migrating to the Movies: Cinema and Black Urban Modernity|year=2005|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley|isbn=0-520-23350-6|page=[https://archive.org/details/migratingtomovie0000stew/page/1 1]|url=https://archive.org/details/migratingtomovie0000stew/page/1}}</ref> and the idiom was common in literature and film during the 1920s and 1930s. Examples include the original 1927 version of the [[Hardy Boys]] book ''[[The House on the Cliff]]'' (pg. 77), where Frank Hardy uses the expression (removed when the story was revised in 1959), and the old-time band [[Skillet Lickers]] recording a song called \"Nigger in the Woodpile\" in 1930.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/skillet-lickers-vol-4-1929-1930-mw0000007207|title=Skillet Lickers, Vol. 4: 1929\u20131930 \u2013 The Skillet Lickers \u2013 Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards \u2013 AllMusic|author=Steve Leggett|publisher=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\n[[Dr. Seuss]] used the term in a 1929 cartoon \"Cross-Section of The World's Most Prosperous Department Store\", wherein customers browse through a department store looking for items to make their lives more difficult. The panels show a series of scenarios based on popular figures of speech: a man with a net trying to catch a [[fly in the ointment|fly for his ointment]], another looking at [[monkeywrenching|monkey wrenches to throw into his machinery]], one examining [[needle in a haystack (disambiguation)|haystacks with matching needles]], and finally a man looking at a selection of niggers for his woodpile.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/05/27/racist-dr-seuss_n_7446806.html|title=One Particularly Upsetting And Racist Dr. Seuss Cartoon Is Heading To Auction|first=Priscilla|last=Frank|date=27 May 2015|work=Huff Post}}</ref>\n\nThe author Zane Grey's 1921 novel ''The Mysterious Rider'' uses the expression at least twice throughout the story to explain a situation in which facts were purposefully omitted.\nIn the 1929 RKO film \"Street Girl,\" the phrase is spoken by [[Joseph Cawthorn]], but it has been erased from the print that Turner Classic Movies shows.\n\nIn the 1930 [[pre-Code]] comedy ''[[Not So Dumb]]'', Marion Davies consistently and constantly convolutes common idioms and expressions. After finally finding misplaced billiard balls that she had used as darning eggs, she proudly exclaims, \"I just knew there was a woodpile in the nigger when I couldn't find 'em.\"{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n\nA visual gag in the [[Looney Tunes]] cartoon ''[[Porky's Railroad]]'' from 1937 refers to the phrase.\n\nThe phrase is also used in ''[[The Razor's Edge]]'' by [[Somerset Maugham]]. One of the American characters, on the brink of closing a business deal, says to the narrator, \"I'll fly down to Texas to give the outfit the once-over, and you bet I'll keep my eyes peeled for a nigger in the woodpile before I cough up any ... dough.\"<ref>The Razor's Edge (Vintage International) (Part Seven, Chapter 3, p. 244).</ref>\n\n\nIn Chapter 3 of ''[[Absalom, Absalom]]'' William Faulkner uses the phrase when referring to the success of a cotton plantation: \"...some among his fellow citizens who believed even yet that there was a nigger in the woodpile somewhere.\" <ref>{{Cite book|title=Absalom, Absalom! : the corrected text|last=1897-1962.|first=Faulkner, William|date=1993|publisher=Modern Library|isbn=0679600728|edition= 1993 Modern Library |location=New York|pages=72|oclc=28378575}}</ref>\n\nComputer scientist [[Edsger W. Dijkstra]] uses the phrase in a published reply to referees ca 1975.\n<ref> https://www.cs.utexas.edu/users/EWD/transcriptions/EWD04xx/EWD470.html\n</ref>\n\nIn the book ''Your Health: A Corrective System of Exercising that Revolutionizes the Entire Field of Physical Education'', by Joseph H. Pilates in 1934, page 18 writes, \"This is the 'Nigger in the wood pile'.\"<ref>Pilates, Joseph H., (1934) Your Health: A Corrective System of Exercising that Revolutionizes the Entire Field of Physical Education. Published by Joseph H. Pilates.</ref>\n\nAgatha Christie used the phrase as the title of chapter 18 of the 1937 [[Hercule Poirot]] novel ''[[Dumb Witness]]'', which was later published in the U.S. as ''Poirot Loses a Client''. The chapter was later retitled \"A Cuckoo in the Nest\". A character also uses the phrase in Chapter 22 of her 1953 book \"After the Funeral\". The phrase was also used by a character in early editions of Christie's novel ''[[And Then There Were None]]'' (originally released under the title ''Ten Little Niggers''), but was changed in later editions to ''There's a [[fly in the ointment]]''. As late as 1952, in the novel ''[[They Do It with Mirrors]]'', published in the U.S. as ''Murder with Mirrors,'' she has a character use the phrase. It appears in editions published as late as 1985.  In her 1970 novel ''[[Passenger to Frankfurt]]'', she has a character use the phrase in chapter 23.\n\n[[W. C. Fields]] used variations of this phrase in two of his films: In ''[[You Can't Cheat an Honest Man]]'' (1939) he said there was \"an Ubangi in the fuel supply\", and in ''[[My Little Chickadee]]'' (1940) he said there was \"an Ethiopian in the fuel supply\".\n\nIn the song, \"This Could Be True\", [[Pat Kirkwood (actress)|Pat Kirkwood]] and [[Graham Payn]] sing the phrase in [[No\u00ebl Coward]]'s 1950 musical ''[[Ace of Clubs (musical)|Ace of Clubs]]''.\n\nPopular western author [[Louis L'Amour]] used a variant in ''Crossfire Trail'' (1954): \"Now there seemed to be a larger African in the woodpile, or several of them.\"\n\nPopular music group [[Supertramp]] used the phrase in the lyrics of their 1971 song 'Potter'. English band [[10cc]] also used the phrase in their song 'The Second Sitting for the Last Supper' from their album [[The Original Soundtrack]] from 1975.\n\nThe phrase declined in use during the 20th century, and now the occasional use of this phrase by public figures has often been followed by controversy and apology.\n\nIn July 2008, the leader of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|British Conservative Party]], [[David Cameron]], was urged to sack Conservative peer [[Lord Dixon-Smith]], who said in the [[House of Lords]] that concerns about government housing legislation were \"the nigger in the woodpile\".  Dixon-Smith said the phrase had \"slipped out without my thinking\", and that \"It was common parlance when I was younger\".<ref name=\"cameron\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/2273176/David-Cameron-urged-to-sack-Tory-peer-after-nigger-in-the-woodpile-remark.html|title=David Cameron urged to sack Tory peer after 'nigger in the woodpile' remark \u2013 David Cameron is facing calls to sack a Conservative peer who described concerns over government housing legislation as \"the nigger in the woodpile\" during a House of Lords debate.|author=Lucy Cockcroft|website=The Daily Telegraph|date=9 July 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, the phrase was again used by British Conservative Party politician [[Anne Marie Morris]] who said that [[Brexit]] without a deal with the European Union was the \"real nigger in the woodpile\". She later said \"The comment was totally unintentional. I apologise unreservedly for any offence caused.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40555639|title=MP Anne Marie Morris apologises for racist remark|date=10 July 2017|publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-brexiteer-uk-leaving-eu-without-deal-n-word-in-the-woodpile-anne-marie-morris-newton-abbott-a7833786.html|title=Tory Brexiteer describes UK leaving EU without deal as 'real n***** in the woodpile'|date=10 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/tory-mp-racist-brexit-recording_uk_59638608e4b02e9bdb0e2c77?|title=Listen As Tory MP Recorded Saying Brexit No Deal Is A 'N***** In A Woodpile'|date=10 July 2017}}</ref> However, she was suspended the same day by the party's [[chief whip]], on the orders of party leader, the prime minister, [[Theresa May]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jul/10/tories-urgently-investigating-after-mp-uses-n-word-at-public-event|title=Theresa May orders Tory MP to be suspended after using N-word |date=10 July 2017|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The Conservative Party whip was restored to Morris on 12 December 2017, one day before a crucial vote on the Brexit process. Although Morris voted with the Conservative Government, the Government was defeated by four votes.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Anne Marie Morris: Tory MP has whip restored after racist remark | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42322022 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 12 December 2017 | access-date = 12 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2018 it was revealed that Irish race car driver and commentator [[Derek Daly]] had used the phrase in a radio interview in 1980.  He did so while describing how he was the only non-American on his new race team. Once it was revealed, Derek lost his commentator job. His son also lost his sponsor for the weekend.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jalopnik.com/conor-daly-loses-weekend-nascar-sponsorship-after-dads-1828590727|title=Conor Daly Loses Weekend NASCAR Sponsorship After Dad's Reported Use of the N-Word|last=King|first=Alanis|work=Jalopnik|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[Australian Communications and Media Authority]] (ACMA) ruled that radio station [[2GB]] breached the Commercial Radio Code of Practice when the broadcaster [[Alan Jones (radio broadcaster)|Alan Jones]] used a \"racially charged phrase\" during a segment in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-03-29/sydney-news-morning-briefing-friday-march-29/10950098|title=Jones used 'racially charged phrase'|date=29 March 2019|publisher=ABC News Australia}}</ref> ACMA received numerous complaints after Jones used the controversial phrase in August 2018, while discussing the looming second [[Liberal Party of Australia]] leadership spill. \"The nigger in the woodpile here, if one can use that expression \u2013 and I'm not going to yield to people who tell us that certain words in the language are forbidden \u2013 the person who's playing hard to get is [[Mathias Cormann]],\" Jones told listeners. ACMA found that, while the phrase was widely considered racist, its use in the broadcast didn't likely incite \"hatred\", \"serious contempt\" or \"severe ridicule\". 2GB's management agreed the term will not be used on-air again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acma.gov.au/theACMA/2GB-breaches-decency-requirements|title=2GB breaches decency requirements|date=28 March 2019|publisher=Australian Communications and Media Authority}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, a Downing Street aide alleged that [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York]] had used the phrase during a trade meeting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/nov/18/prince-andrew-used-n-word-former-no-10-aide-claims|title=Prince Andrew used the N-word, former No 10 aide claims|first=Jim Waterson Media|last=editor|date=18 November 2019|via=www.theguardian.com|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[The Dog in the Manger|Dog in the manger]]\n* [[Elephant in the room]]\n* [[Wolf in sheep's clothing]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wiktionary}}\n*[http://loc.harpweek.com/LCPoliticalCartoons/DisplayCartoonMedium.asp?MaxID=&UniqueID=4&Year=1860&YearMark= Racist parody of Republican platform] from 1860 Presidential campaign, in ''[[Harper's Weekly]]''\n*[http://www.utpjournals.com/product/utq/714/714_cariou.htm Epistemology of the Woodpile], ''[[University of Toronto]] Quarterly''\n*[http://hnn.us/articles/1828.html#11130301 History News Network blog post] about origins of term\n*[http://hnn.us/articles/1368.html#11180302 History News Network blog post] about a recent controversy\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=nlgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA72&#v=onepage&q&f=false Phrase used in 1918 advertisement for Patterson Publishing Company] The Rotarian magazine\n\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1840s]]\n[[Category:English phrases]]\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for people]]\n[[Category:Metaphors referring to people]]\n[[Category:Negro]]\n[[Category:American English idioms]]\n", "name_user": "Joel1272", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eUsage:Link correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nigger_in_the_woodpile"}
